<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Direct Foreign Investments in Egypt Shoot Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Direct foreign investments in
Egypt are expected to top 1.5 billion U.S. dollars by the end of
this year, a 67 percent hike from last year, the Middle East News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Minister of Economy Youssef Boutros Ghali as telling
economic editors that the rise is due to the government's credible
economic policies, international recognition of Egypt's economic
performance and it burgeoning money market.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investments in Egypt rose from 432 million
dollars in 1995 to 900 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Egyptian economy is strong enough to lure
investments and impregnable to damages of what he described as "a
single incident."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the shooting and petrol bomb attack on
foreign tourists in central Cairo on September 18 which killed
nine German tourists and an Egyptian driver and wounded eight
other.
</P>
<P>
"The attack on a tourist bus will not affect this field because
investors are fully convinced that it was a single act," he added.
</P>
<P>
Fearing the attack might ruin its multi-billion-dollar tourism
industry and investment environment, Egypt has been quick to claim
it was an isolated incident that had nothing to do with organized
Islamic militant attacks prevalent in Egypt in the early 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
