<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Rolls out TV Ratings System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Canadian TV networks and cable
channels are rolling out national ratings system, starting this
week.
</P>
<P>
The TV ratings system is a method of classifying most TV shows
to alert parents about the levels of violence, sexual content and
coarse language they or their children can expect to meet.
</P>
<P>
When a show begins to be broadcast, a small icon will appear
for about 15 seconds in the upper-left corner of the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
Each icon symbolizes one of six ratings categories, ranging
from C, for children under eight, up to 18, for adult 18 and
older.
</P>
<P>
News, sports, documentaries and other non-dramatic shows are
exempt from the system.
</P>
<P>
Most of Canada's big public and private networks began airing
the icons yesterday. Other broadcast services may take a few weeks
to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
The new system makes Canada "number one in the world" among
countries that classify or control programming, according to Trina
McQueen, president of the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the present ratings are only a temporary measure, which is
likely to be phased out once a more comprehensive system of
household control, the "V-chip", falls into place.
</P>
<P>
The V-chip is a Canadian-invented technology that will permit
parents to program their TVs to black out any shows that parents
deem inappropriate for their children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
