<HEADLINE> Russia Issues New Passports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Russia began to issue new
passports today to replace that of the dissolved Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony marking the issuance of passports, Russian
President Boris Yeltsin said the event is of great significance,
because Russia should have its own passports. Passports issued by
the former Soviet Union are still in use nationwide so far.
</P>
<P>
Local reports say the issuance of new passports will proceed in
three stages: Approximately 4.5 million passports will be
published from October 1 to the end of the year; 10 million
passports will be issued in 1998, and 200 million from 1999 to
December 31, 2005.
</P>
<P>
The project's cost is estimated at 2.5 trillion roubles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
