<HEADLINE> Peace in Afghanistan Vital to Tajikistan: Rahmonov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Tajikistan has joined
international efforts to seek peace in neighboring Afghanistan as
it is in vital interests of Tajikistan, said President Emomali
Rahmonov here today.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly speaking, the unsettled nature of the Afghan problem
may undermine the fragile peace in Tajikistan," he told the
on-going 52nd session of the General Assembly of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
"We are participating in meetings on Afghanistan that have been
conducted laterly by the U.N. Secretary-General among states
concerned and we support proposals on initiation of a broad
intra-Afghan dialogue, as well as on convening an international
peace conference on Afghanistan under the U.N. auspices," he said.
</P>
<P>
The peace in Afghanistan "would also help to substantially reduce
the flow of arms and drugs across the Tajik-Afghan border and the
proliferation of terrorism and extremism waves which destabilize
the whole region," he added.
</P>
<P>
Rahmonov said a coordinated international effort to check drug
trafficking in Central Asia is necessary and Tajikistan supports
conducting a special session of the U.N. General Assembly on drug
problems in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
