<HEADLINE> PNA to Build More Houses for Low Income Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) said here today that PNA is
to build more houses for low income families in several housing
projects.
</P>
<P>
According to the Middle East News Agency, PNA Minister of
Housing Abdul Rahman Hamad called on Arab countries to help fund
the projects to meet the needs of the Palestinian population
growth and to improve the infrastructures of the planned
residential towns.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Arab reporters, the minister noted the initiative
of the United Arab Emirates President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan
Al-Nahyan to finance the construction of two residential towns in
Gaza Strip and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The cost for building the one in Gaza is estimated at 200
million U.S. dollars, Hamad said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Saudi Minister of Public Works and Housing Prince
Moutib Bin Abdel-Aziz has also promised to support the
Saudi-financed Palestinian housing projects.
</P>
<P>
Hamad said that the Palestinian Ministry of Housing has began
technical studies for the two projects, whose construction work he
hoped could start in the first quarter of next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
