<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Continue Efforts on Nuclear Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Russia would like to continue
its efforts to reduce the number of nuclear weapons under the
U.S.-Russian nuclear arms reduction treaty, Russian Minister of
Atomic Energy Viktor Mikhailov said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 40th annual conference of the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), Mikhailov reiterated that Russia
would adhere to the principles of nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
In 1995-1997, Russia used 36 tons of enriched uranium for
nuclear power plants and it plans to up the figure to 156 by the
year 2000, Mikhailov said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russia will invest 100-150 million U.S. dollars per
year to improve safety devices in nuclear power plants, the
minister added.
</P>
<P>
As for the START-II nuclear arms reduction treaty, he said
Russia and the U.S. signed an accord last week in New York urging
the Russian State Duma (the lower house of parliament) to ratify the
treaty, which was signed between the two countries in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The treaty has been stalled for four years in Russia's
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The treaty sets a warhead limit of 3,500 on each side, down
from about 8,000, and strips Russia of its most powerful missile,
the SS-18.
</P>
<P>
Mikhailov also noted that Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
his U.S. counterpart, Bill Clinton, recently reached an agreement
on basic principles for the START-III treaty, which will undergo
negotiations once the START-II is ratified in Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Aide Convicted of Smuggling Drugs to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- A Miami federal court has
convicted a top aide to Venezuela's former anti-drug chief of
conspiring to ship up to 22 tons of cocaine to Florida, reports
reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The verdict against Adolfo Romero Gomez, who was extradited
from Colombia a year ago, was announced late on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The jury deliberated 12 hours over two days but remained
deadlocked on another charge, accusing Romero of smuggling a
shipment of more than 900 pounds of cocaine from Colombia through
Venezuela to the United States in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The sentence is scheduled for December 10 and Romero, who is in
his 60s, faces life in prison.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said Romero and his boss, Gen. Ramon Guillen
Davila, betrayed the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency and Drug
Enforcement Administration agents who worked with them.
</P>
<P>
Convicted drug smugglers testified that Romero acted as a
middleman between Colombian cocaine suppliers and Florida
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
CIA and DEA agents also testified that Romero smuggled tons of
cocaine into the United States in 1990 and 1991 without telling
U.S. authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
