<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgrade Mayor Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Zoran Djinpjic, mayor of
Belgrade, capital of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, was
relieved of his duties for abuse of power after a secrete ballot
by the city's parliament today.
</P>
<P>
Among the 68 legislators present at the vote, 67 voted for
Djinpjic's dismissal. Some 36 legislators from the Democratic
Party of Serbia, headed by Djinpjic, refused to attend the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
As Novinska Agencija Tanjug reported, the motion was
proposed by the Serbian Renewal Movement.
</P>
<P>
About two months earlier, another party, Serbian Socialist
Party, proposed to the 110-strong city parliament, a motion to
impeach Djinpjic, though the motion was aborted due to a majority
vote against it at the time.
</P>
<P>
As Chairman of the Democratic Party of Serbia, one of the major
opposition parties, Djinpjic was elected mayor of Belgrade in last
year's regional elections.
</P>
<P>
At today's vote, Djinpjic was charged with abuse of power in
the interest of his own party.
</P>
<P>
Djinpjic's Democratic Party and the Serbian Renewal Movement
headed by Vuk Drasskovic, used to be allies of the opposition
union.
</P>
<P>
However, the competition between Djinpjic and Drasskovic for
the candidacy for the presidential election broke up the alliance
and made the two parties rivals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
