<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq to Cut Food Rations from October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Food rations for Iraqi people
will be cut as from October due to short supplies, according to
the Iraqi news agency (INA) today.
</P>
<P>
INA said an official source of the Ministry of Commerce blamed
the cut on U.S. obstructing and delaying the approval of the
contracts Iraq signed with foreign companies under the
oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said cereals ration will be cut from one kilogram
to 400 grams and edible oil from one kilogram to 250 grams. The
third item is soap, but the amount is unknown.
</P>
<P>
The rations for an adult Iraq per month include at nine
kilograms of flour, 2.5 kilograms of rice, two kilograms of sugar,
150 grams of tea, one kilogram of cereals, one kilogram of edible
oil, 350 grams of washing powder and 250 grams of soap.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Haleidy, U.N. humanitarian affairs coordinator in Iraq,
said last week that Iraq had received 90 percent of the food items
contracted within the framework of the first phase of the
oil-for-food deal which ended in June.
</P>
<P>
The deal, signed in May 1996 and put into force last December,
allows Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over a
six-month period to buy food, medicines and other humanitarian
goods. It was renewed in June this year.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi people have been suffering from the six-year-old
U.N. sanctions imposed following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been accusing the U.S. of obstructing the
implementation of the deal. It claimed that some of the contracts
still have not been approved by the U.N. Sanctions Committee due
to U.S. hindrance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
