<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Backs EU Membership for Turkey in Principle, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 30 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
told visiting Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz that Germany
supports an eventual membership for Turkey in the European Union
(EU) but first expects Ankara to make its own contributions toward
this goal, a German government spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
"Chancellor Kohl declared that he supported the goal of a later
Turkish membership in the EU and expected Turkey to follow EU
demands to make its own contributions in order to reach this
goal," said Kohl's spokesman Peter Hausmann after a meeting
between Kohl and Yilmaz today in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, Kohl had made Turkey's future EU
membership dependent on, among other things, a solution of
Ankara's dispute with Greece over the divided island of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz told reporters after the meeting that he was satisfied
with his talks in Bonn and he saw "a turning point" in Turkey's
relations with the EU.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the EU's selection of Poland, Hungary, the
Czech Republic, Slovenia, Estonia as well as Cyprus as the top
candidates for its enlargement and expressed the confident that
Turkey would not be excluded from the process at EU's next summit
due in December.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said he would hold intensive talks with other EU
governments in the run-up to the summit and would reconvene with
Kohl in Bonn in December.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the talks, Turkish and German officials
today also signed an agreement on setting up a German-language
university in Istanbul in an effort to promote the cultural
relations between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
