<HEADLINE> King Hussein: Jordan Never Allow Terrorist Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today affirmed its
determination to counter terrorist acts which culminated in the
past week in consecutive attacks on two Israeli embassy guards and
a Hamas leader.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan would never allow anybody to turn this country into a
base for acts of terrorism in any form or shape," King Hussein
said today while addressing a public gathering in southwest to
capital Amman, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
On the morning of September 22, two Israeli embassy guards here
were shot and wounded by unidentified gunmen; and on September 25,
Khalid Mashiel, head of the political bureau of the Islamic
Resistance Movement, Hamas, was beaten into coma by two Canadian
tourists in front of his office here.
</P>
<P>
The king urged his countrymen to cooperate and work together
with the government to face up to coming challenges.
</P>
<P>
While investigations of the two attacks are now underway and
the attackers of the September 22 case remain at large, public
fear of new eruption of violence has been making headlines in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The wounded Israeli diplomats was immediately treated in local
hospitals, and later sent back to Israel for further therapy.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas leader is now hospitalized in the King Hussein
Medical Center under Hussein's instruction and confirmed to be in
"stable condition" by a Jordanian official.
</P>
<P>
The two Canadian tourists who beat Mashiel are now in custody
for investigation. Hamas has accused the Israeli secret
intelligence Mossad of implication in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was established in 1987 to fight against Israel`s
occupation of Palestine. Most Hamas political bureau members live
in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, becoming one
of the countries in the Arab world that have normalized relations
with the Jewish state. The other country is Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
