<HEADLINE> Kinshasa Bombing Cuts Short kabila's Visit to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Laurent Kabila, President of
the Democratic Republic of Congo, today cut short of his
scheduled three-day official visit to Zambia and returned home.
</P>
<P>
Kabila rushed back to his country after 17 people were killed
Monday in Kinshasa as a result of shellings from Brazzaville,
capital of the Republic of Congo, across the River Congo.
</P>
<P>
The visiting president, who arrived here Monday on his first
visit abroad after he took power from late Mobutu Sese Seko in
May, is supposed to visit the Copperbelt province today and fly
home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Shells fired from Brazzaville landed in Kinshasa again today as
the former Zaire held a National Day of mourning for the victims,
according to the reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Around 20 shells hit Kinshasa, which is separated with
Brazaville by the Congo River, during a second day of heavy
artillery exchanges in Brazzaville between supporters of
President Pascal Lissouba and his predecessor Denis Sassou
Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately clear who was firing the shells.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the incident at a banquet for him by Zambian
President Frederick Chiluba last night, Kabila disclosed that
security in his country is threatened by soldiers of the former
government who, after running away after the fall of Mobutu's
regime, have re-grouped and are posing a threat to people's life.
</P>
<P>
"If the provocation persists, we may be forced to take action
to silence the mortars," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila added that he wants an explanation from Brazaville that
why Kinshasa is being bombed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
