<HEADLINE> German Finance Minister Sees 1 Billion Mark Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 30 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo
Waigel today said that German taxpayers could only expect a net
tax cut of up to one billion German marks (565 million U.S.
dollars) next year through a planned reduction in the so-called
"solidarity" income tax.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's ruling coalition has agreed to
cut the unpopular 7.5-percent solidarity surcharge from January
next year after a broader tax reform package was buried by the
main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) last week.
</P>
<P>
The solidarity tax was imposed after the 1990 German
reunification to finance the reconstruction of eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
However, a two-percent cut in that tax, as requested by Kohl's
junior coalition partner, the Free Democratic Party (FDP), would
rip a 7.5 billion mark (4.2 billion dollar) hole in next year's
budget, a shortfall that remains unfinanced without the broader
tax package.
</P>
<P>
A government consultation presided by Kohl today in Bonn had
apparently failed to find a reasonable solution to the problem.
But Waigel told reporters that he expected a decision on the issue
before November.
</P>
<P>
Officials emerging from the talks disclosed that the government
was considering further sales of state assets to help
counter-finance the tax cut.
</P>
<P>
As their subsidy-fueled economy is slowing down to a nearly
standstill at present, eastern German leaders of Kohl's party have
vowed to resist any attempt to cut subsidies to their regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
