<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-30 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Rivals to Exchange Info on Missing People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Greek Cypriot side is
ready to hand over information about 200 Turkish Cypriots and 15
Greek Cypriots missing in the conflicts two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides made the announcement
today at his daily press briefing. He said Cypriot government is
ready to comply with an agreement reached by the leaders of the
two communities in July.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash agreed "to provide the other side immediately and
simultaneously with all information already at their disposal on
the location of graves."
</P>
<P>
The exchange of information was set by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
"The information will be handed over in a responsible manner
and we expect the other side to respond in the same way, so we can
put an end to this tragic problem," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Since inter-communal clashes began in the early 1960s, at least
500 Turkish Cypriots have been reported missing; and 1,619 Greek
Cypriots were listed as missing after Turkey intervened by landing
its troops on the Mediterranean in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said the information gathered from witness reports
and statements will have to be substantiated with scientific
evidence on every missing person's identity.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and occupied the northern third of the island to protect
the Turkish Cypriots following a failed coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The issue of missing people has been one of the main issues of
the protracted Cyprus problem, which has remained unsolved despite
the U.N. and international community's peace efforts in the past
23 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Impose Traffic Control in Paris to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The French government will
impose an open-ended tough traffic control in Paris and some towns
around it on Wednesday to reduce pollution, which hit a record
high in nearly two years today.
</P>
<P>
All primary schools in Paris region today cancelled physical
and sports classes because of heavy pollution, and police
tightened speed limit in the city to 20 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
From 05:30 a.m. until 22:00 p.m. Wednesday, only vehicles with
odd registration numbers can circulate in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The pollution level hit level three, or more than 400
micrograms of dioxide nitrogen in each cubic meter, today in
Paris, the highest since November 8, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Environment Dominique Voynet, who is the
president of the Green Party, proposed the measure to the welcome
of ruling leftwing parties and opposition from the opposition
right.
</P>
<P>
She said that it is difficult to predict how many days the
control will be in force in Paris, which has been having clear
days with full sunshine for many weeks.
</P>
<P>
She said that a cloudy or rainy day could help reduce the
pollution level to below level three, in which case the control
will be lifted.
</P>
<P>
The measure is backed by a 1996 national law on air cleanness
and a regional decree in the Paris region adopted by local
councillors in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who breaks the decree will be fined 900 francs (150 U.S.
dollars), said police.
</P>
<P>
Only small cars carrying fewer than tree persons, public
transport vehicles, taxis and vehicles serving certain kinds of
professions are spared from the control.
</P>
<P>
The southcentral city Lyon adopted similar traffic control on
heavy trucks on January 16-18, after the metropolis was hit by a
pollution above level three for days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: Programs for Older Persons Must Be Integral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Programs for older
persons must be part of development planning, the U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan stressed here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion of the International Day of Older
Persons, The Secretary-General said a society for all ages was one
that recognized the rights and responsibilities of all group
persons. It was one in which old persons could live healthy,
productive, economically secure lives. It was one that adjusted
its policies and plans to the needs and capabilities of all,
thereby releasing the potential of all, for the benefit of all.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said that the General Assembly had taken
several significant initiatives concerning the rights and the
welfare of older persons. In 1982, the Assembly endorsed the
International Plan of Action on Aging. In 1991, it adopted the
United Nations Principles for Older Persons.
</P>
<P>
Annan said with the aging of individuals and populations in
developed and developing countries alike, the world faced a
two-fold challenge. First was the promotion of lifelong
individuals development, so that individuals could reach old age
with life skills, vocational skills, good health and good family
and social network. Second was the creation of an enabling and
encouraging environment in which individuals of all ages could
participate actively and receive care and support when needed.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation of women bore special mention. Women
everywhere were living longer than men. Women were also likely
than men to be poorer in old age for various reasons. Ensuring
economic security for older women must be a major focus of our
work.
</P>
<P>
Annan added the United Nations had consistently promoted the
fullest possible participation of older persons in society and the
fullest possible recognition of their needs and concerns.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed that as the world's demographic transition
proceeds, efforts should be redoubled to make policies and
programs for older persons an integral part of overall
development strategies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
