<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Measures against Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton Tuesday outlined a couple of steps to enhance the battle
against housing discrimination, which he admitted was worse than
he had believed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton named a total of 67 public and private local agencies
that will receive a total of 15 million dollars in federal grants
to combat housing discrimination.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also outlined plans for the federal government to
double its number of housing discrimination enforcement actions
over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
The president made the announcement at a meeting of his race
advisory board, saying, "It's clear to me now that there is more
housing discrimination in America than I had thought there was
when I became president." He said that has been keeping "too many
families from sending their children to the schools of their
choice."
</P>
<P>
Administration officials said the nationwide rate of home
ownership is near its record high, with minority owners accounting
for 29 percent of all new home buyers from 1993 to 1996. But
officials said the number of complaints of housing discrimination
have increased along with the growth in minority participation.
</P>
<P>
The 15 million-dollar grant will consist primarily of a 10.2
million dollar share for enforcement organizations that
investigate allegations of housing discrimination, provide housing
counseling and promote fair housing.
</P>
<P>
The grant money, from the federal budget for the fiscal year
that ends today, also includes money to help build such
organizations, and to promote reconciliation in racially troubled
communities where minority groups move into formerly all-white
areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
