<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fed Decides to Hold Interest Rates Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
(Fed) decided today to hold short-term interest rates steady as
the inflation in the country remains well under control.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed apparently opted instead to watch and wait for
more signs of inflation which was now in the best performance in
three decades.
</P>
<P>
The decision had been widely expected given the near absence of
price pressures despite robust economic growth and the lowest
unemployment rate in 24 years.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. central bank announced this afternoon that it had
adjourned a closed-door meeting of its policy-making Federal Open
Market Committee (FOMC) and had nothing further to say. It meant
the FOMC had left the federal fund rate, the rate governing
overnight loans between banks, unchanged at 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
An increase would have raised borrowing costs for millions of
American consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
The Fed hasn't changed the benchmark rate since March 25 when
it raised it by a quarter percentage point to curb potential
excessive demand that could fan inflation. The U.S. economy has
continued to expand strongly since then but inflation has
improved.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices increased at an annual rate of 1.6 percent in
the first eight months, less than half of the 3.3 percent in last
year. And the prices excluding the volatile energy and food costs
rose at 2.2 percent rate, down from 2.6 percent last year and the
best since 1965.
</P>
<P>
U.S. economic analysts say that how soon the Fed will raise the
interest rates all depends on whether economic growth moderates
enough to ease strain on factory capacity and the labor supply. It
also depends on the explanation for the good luck on inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
