<HEADLINE> 17 People in Kinshasa Killed in Congolese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Seventeen people have been
killed in the Democratic Republic of Congo's capital Kinshasa in
renewed intensified fighting in neighboring Republic of Congo,
according to sources monitored here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that military forces in Kinshasa responded by
firing artillery shots across the Congo River separating the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The authorities in the Democratic Republic of Congo said they
wanted an explanation from the Congolese government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, the police in the Democratic Republic of
Congo had already closed three Congo River crossing points and
ordered refugees from the Congolese capital Brazzaville to
register with the authorities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Congolese President Pascal Lissouba said he has
sent a ceasefire proposal to international mediators in the
conflict with his rival former president Sassou Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
Lissouba also said the crisis in the country will not hamper
the democratic process. He declared that presidential election
will take place in the country within 15 months despite the
crisis which is still going on.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese authorities said the fighting in Brazzaville has
killed at least 4,000 people since it broke out in June. 
</P>
