<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to lift Emergency Rule in Southeastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish government today
decided to lift the 10-year-old emergency rule imposed on three
southeastern provinces, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made at a Council of Ministers meeting
chaired by Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit earlier today.
</P>
<P>
The government wants the emergency rule to come to an end in
Batman, Bingol and Bitlis, Government Spokesman Sukru Sina Gurel
told a press conference following the meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has to get parliament approval of the
decision before it takes effect. The parliament is expected to
discuss this proposal soon, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The emergency rule was imposed on nine southeastern provinces
to combat the separatist movement of the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK). The rule gave the army and police more powers to
arrest the PKK rebels.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 13-year-old war against the
Turkish authorities in a bid to establish an independent Kurdish
state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
More than 27,000 people, including soldiers, rebels and
civilians, have been killed in the armed conflicts between the
government troops and the PKK militants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
