<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Congress Votes to Keep Government Running </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate voted
today to keep the government running into the new fiscal year
while lawmakers finish spending legislation.
</P>
<P>
With fiscal 1998 beginning on October 1, the U.S. Senate voted
99-0 to let government agencies function through October 23 and
shipped the measure to the White House for Clinton's certain
signature.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives also approved the bill
overwhelmingly Monday with a vote of 355-57.
</P>
<P>
The legislation is needed because the U.S. Congress has sent
only three of the 13 annual spending bills to the White House and
none of them has been signed by the U.S. president as yet.
</P>
<P>
The bill temporarily finances programs at 1997 levels, except
for those that lawmakers and the president have agreed to cut. The
stopgap bill will be signed by President Clinton soon as expected.
</P>
<P>
Even though there are some disputes on items in several
spending bills of fiscal 1998, the Republicans and Democrats in
the Congress are cooperating in a spirit that was lacking for the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, the beginning of the new fiscal year was marked
by a bitter budget stalemate between Clinton and Republicans. That
fight produced two partial government shutdowns totaling 27 days.
Republicans in the U.S. Congress were overwhelmingly blamed by the
public for provoking the battle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
