<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Prime Minister on Education Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRIGHTON, England, September 30 (Xinhua) -- British Prime
Minister Tony Blair delivered today a package of education reforms
to fulfill his election pledge of education being its government's
"top priority."
</P>
<P>
He told the Labor Party Conference about a 2 billion pound (3.2
billion US dollar) rescue package to renovate rundown classrooms
and equip every school with the latest computers and a drive for
even higher numeracy and literacy standards at primary level.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said, "The biggest assault on poor literacy
and numeracy standards this country has seen: Nearly 40 percent of
11 year olds can't read, write or add up properly."
</P>
<P>
Britain is now at "the 42nd in the world education league," he
admitted.
</P>
<P>
"This is the scandalous legacy not just of 18 years of the Tory
government but of a country too often content to educate the elite
and ignore education for all," he added.
</P>
<P>
In order to reverse the "scandalous" trend, Blair set "a target
of 80 percent up to the standard in literacy, 75 percent for
numeracy by the year 2002."
</P>
<P>
He said that the aim of the education reforms is to give "every
11-year-old the start in life they deserve."
</P>
<P>
The huge cash injection is the center-piece of an ambitious
three-point drive to improve education.
</P>
<P>
Blair announced that every one of the country's 33,000 schools
will have the latest computers within five years.
</P>
<P>
Analyists here believe that the move underlines Blair's
commitment to make education his government's passion and give
Britain the world's best-trained workforce.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said, "We will never be the biggest country,
we may never be the mightiest, but we can be the best."
</P>
<P>
Blair warned that teacher training would be reformed. Head
teachers would have a proper qualification. "Poor teachers will
go," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed, "Don't let anybody think that we
are tough on bad teaching because we don't value teachers."
</P>
<P>
"We are tough on bad teachers precisely because we do value
good teachers," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
