<HEADLINE> Blair Announces 1998 Is UK NetYear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRIGHTON, England, September 30 (Xinhua) -- November will see
the launch of UK NetYear, an on-going high-profile program
designed to raise awareness of the potential of the Internet as an
education tool, according to a press release issued by the Labor
Party Conference.
</P>
<P>
UK NetYear was given government support today as part of a
package of education initiatives in Prime Minister Tony Blair's
first speech to the Conference.
</P>
<P>
Schools across the UK need both the technology, and the
teachers trained to use it, to equip children with the skills they
need to excel in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
At present only some 6,000 schools in the UK are connected to
the Internet. The aim of UK NetYear is to increase this total to
17,000 by the end of 1998, and in conjunction with the National
Grid for Learning to have all 32,000 schools on the "Net" by 2002.
</P>
<P>
UK NetYear will motivate local communities and businesses to
become involved in the process, not only in sponsorship and
fund raising but also guidance for schools, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
UK NetYear will involve leading companies in the computing and
communications sectors, experienced in the application of
technology for the needs of society.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the program, the UK NetYear board's Executive
Chairman, David Wimpress, said, "We are determined that our
industry will make every effort to help school governors,
teachers, pupils and parents fully utilized the significant
potential of Information and Communication Technology to enhance
educational attainment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
