<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Is No Threat to its Neighbors, Powell Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- General Colin L. Powell,
former Chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff said here today
he does not believe China is a threat to its neighbors despite
efforts to modernize its military.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the so-called China Threat allegation at a
press conference after his keynote speech at the 1997 Citibank
Asian Leadership Series, Powell said, "It's something to watch. I
watch because it is too early to worry."
</P>
<P>
He said that China is modernizing its military because "their
military is so far behind they have to modernize it. We are
modernizing ours and Singapore is modernizing theirs," he added.
</P>
<P>
"China has come to the conclusion that the way to become a more
successful nation is not to threaten its neighbors, but to
participate in the world economic system," said Powell, who served
as a key military advisor to the US president.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Powell stressed that China is becoming a major power
in the world, not because of its ideology or its military force,
but because of it's participation in the globalization of the
world economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
