<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Seeking to Sign Agreement With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, October l (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government is
seeking to sign an agreement with the largest anti-government
rebel group in the south, in a bid to end the 14-year civil war, a
government official has said.
</P>
<P>
The government is ready to accept all the mediations to secure
an agreement with John Garang, leader of the Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), Mohamed Al Amin Khalifa, secretary general
of Sudan's Supreme Peace Council, said in an exclusive interview
published by Sudanese newspaper Akhbar El-Yom today.
</P>
<P>
The government signed a peace agreement with four small
southern rebel factions in Khartoum last April. But the SPLA
refused to join the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Khartoum peace agreement stipulates that the Southerners
would be given the right to self-determination at the end of a
transitional period, Khalifa said.
</P>
<P>
After the four-year transitional period, citizens in the south will
decide by ballot whether they will stay in or to separate from the
country, according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Khalifa said that the government and the SPLA agreed recently
on the venue of a meeting and the number of negotiators from both
parties to the negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Khalifa said that the government is ready to put forward its
own views while listening to ideas of the SPLA delegation on the
future of the country in the coming negotiations scheduled for
October in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA declared its acceptance of the IGADD
(Inter-Governmental Authority on Drought and Development)
"Declaration of Principles" put forward in 1994 for resolving the
southern Sudan question.
</P>
<P>
IGADD, which groups Sudan, Kenya,Uganda, Ethiopia, Eritrea,
Somalia and Djibouti, called for separation of religion from
politics and upholding political pluralism in Sudan in the
"Declaration of Principles".
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has already signed peace agreements
with seven rebel factions in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Over 1 million people have died in violence since 1983 when the
southern rebels took up arms for greater autonomy from the
Islamic north for the Christian and Animist south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
