<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Criminal Proceedings Initiated Against Kokh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Moscow Prosecutor's
Office has initiated criminal proceedings against ex-deputy prime
minister and former head of the State Property Committee Alfred
Kokh on a charge of abuse of office, the Interfax news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Prosecutor of Moscow Yuri Syomin, the
decision was made after the Prosecutor-General's Office submitted
reports claiming that Kokh had received a 100,000 U.S. dollar bribe
from the Swiss company Servina Trading.
</P>
<P>
The reports revealed that in January 1997, the Servina agency
paid Kokh 557.3 million rubles (about 100,000 dollars) for the
right to publish his book on privatization in Russia, which has not
been finished yet.
</P>
<P>
"The number of books that will be printed is expected to be 100
to 4,000 copies at a price not to exceed 15 U.S. dollars a
copy. However, under the agreement, the author received a fee far
in excess of expected revenues," Syomin said.
</P>
<P>
"No responsibility was envisioned in the agreement for the
improper implementation or nonimplementation of obligations by
Kokh," the deputy prosecutor added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Prosecutor's Office has also been informed that
the agreement between Kokh and the Servina agency had been
mediated by Dmitri Ushakov, the vice chairman of the board of
UNEXIM bank.
</P>
<P>
Syomin said the bank wished "to strengthen relations
with Kokh, as a deputy prime minister and the head of the State
Property Committee."
</P>
<P>
Under these circumstances, the Prosecutor's Office today
initiated criminal proceedings against Kokh and launched an
investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
