<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa Urged to Prepare for El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries
have been urged by the World Bank to enhance regional cooperation
to prepare for the early appearance of El Nino, which could cause
a long spell of devastating drought in the region.
</P>
<P>
Regional cooperation is needed, with better forecasting
technology, for the region to be better prepared for the early
approach of El Nino, bank officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There are clearly benefits to integration in the region...
Africa is not even on the map for many investors as a trade area
and that is a concern," said Pamela Cox, World Bank country
director for South Africa, Botswana, Namibia, Lesotho and
Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
He said that there were many cross-border issues in the region
such as water management, transport infrastructure for landlocked
nations, improving communications systems and addressing health
issues such as malaria.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank has identified broad targets for future
assistance. They include encouraging trade links, developing
transport corridors, making capital flow easier and solving water
supply problems.
</P>
<P>
The South African Weather Bureau said it was detecting early
signs of the appearance of El Nino.
</P>
<P>
"The fairly good rains we experienced a few weeks ago,
followed by these very high temperatures (in the past few days),
is an indication of the disturbance in the weather patterns,"
said Mike Edwards, the bureau's deputy director.
</P>
<P>
Normally El Nino did not start causing weather problems in
South Africa before December, but it was known that the El Nino
pattern started early this year.
</P>
<P>
As an indication of the approach of El Nino, a strong heat
wave swept the country in the past few days when summer has
barely begun.
</P>
<P>
At least 13 heat records for September were broken Monday with
temperatures as high as 42.6 being recorded.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's hottest temperature Monday in the Kruger
National Park in the Mpumalanga province was a record high in 35
years.
</P>
<P>
High temperatures were also recorded in the Northern Cape and
Gauteng provinces.
</P>
<P>
"I would not say that this particular heat is an indication
that there is going to be a drought in South Africa... it is an
indication that there is already a disturbance in our weather
patterns," Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
The Pretoria-based weather bureau predicted that hot to very
hot weather will continue in most of the country for the next two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's National Maize Producers' Association, worried
about an early onset of an El Nino drought in southern Africa,
has warned its members to delay planting this year. Early El Nino
could be disastrous in the region, it said.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino weather phenomenon, caused by the warming of
Pacific waters off South America, is already being blamed for
economic turmoil in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
In Southeast Asia, a dry spell has damaged maize crops in
Java, Indonesia, and it is feared that the El Nino effect could
rival that in 1982-83, which cost the world about 13 billion U.S.
Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamas Welcomes Yassin's Release, Vowing to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) today welcomed the release of its founder Sheikh
Ahmed Yassin, while vowing to continue its holy war against Israel
"until the liberation of Palestine."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued following Yassin's release overnight from
Israeli prison and arrival in Jordanian capital Amman, Hamas also
thanked Jordanian King Hussein for his efforts in securing
Yassin's release.
</P>
<P>
"Hamas welcomes the release of the Mujahid Sheikh Ahmed Yassin
from the prison of Zionist enemy. The movement also appreciates
the Jordanian efforts exerted to release him," the Hamas statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Yassin, 61, who founded Hamas in 1987 and has been jailed for
life sentence since 1989, was flown in a Jordanian helicopter to
Amman and transferred to the King Hussein Medical Center for
treatment. He was seriously ill after nine years imprisonment in
Israeli jail, and was wheel chair-bound, paralyzed in arms and
legs, and suffering from breathing and hearing problems.
</P>
<P>
After refusing numerous calls for Yassin's release, Israel
finally decided to free Yassin apparently because of the fear
that his death in Israeli prison could spark a wave of
retaliatory terror attacks by Hamas militants.
</P>
<P>
Hamas, which has been launching a terror campaign to destroy
Israel in order to establish a single Muslim state in the whole
Middle East, has gained fame for its suicide bombing operations
against Israeli targets.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, Hamas has planned a dozen of suicide attacks
inside Israel, killing hundreds of people. It claimed
responsibility for the recent two suicide attacks in Jerusalem's
Mahane Yehud market and Ben Yehuda mall which killed 25 people
and wounded over 300 others.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, King Hussein called on Israel to take positive
steps to help promote the peace process by freeing Yassin from
jail. This provided the excuse for Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to release Yassin.
</P>
<P>
After his arrival in the hospital in Amman today, Yassin gave
a four-minute telephone news conference held in Gaza by local
Hamas leader Abdul Aziz Rantisi. "I send to my greetings to the
entire Palestinian people. I want to inform them that I am coming
back to Gaza in the near future," Yassin said.
</P>
<P>
Rantisi earlier condemned Israel's handling of Yassin's
release, saying Yassin was expelled and not freed by Israel. In
the Gaza news conference, he quoted Yassin as saying that Hamas
will continue its jihad (holy war) "until the end of Israeli
occupation and the return of the total rights of the Palestinian
people."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) officials also criticized
Israel for deporting Yassin instead of allowing him to reunite
with his family in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
PNA Secretary-General Abdul Rahman denounced Israel for not
informing the PNA of Yassin's release. Senior Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat expressed the hope that Yassin would be
allowed to come back to Gaza, adding that Israel should release
all jailed Palestinian prisoners according to signed peace
accords. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
