<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biogas Advised as Energy Source in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1.4 million
megawatts in annual potential electricity can be produced in
Tanzania through biogas from crop wastes, with crude diesel oil
substitution of about 350,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
This is a suggestion by Professor Amelia Kajumulo of the
applied microbiology unit in the Department of Botany at the
University of Tanzania in a research she has conducted.
</P>
<P>
Total oil substitution from residues will be equivalent to two
percent of total energy consumption in the country, on the basis
of case studies conducted at coffee and sisal processing
factories.
</P>
<P>
Amelia Kajumulo said that important agro-industrial residues
and municipal solid wastes with large potentials from anaerobic
conversion into biogas and electricity have been identified and
quantified following intensive research.
</P>
<P>
She said that about 615,000 tons of organic matter is being
generated from coffee, sisal, sugar-cane and cereal residues
while households in major towns generate about 600,000 tons of
organic materials annually.
</P>
<P>
She is of the view that tapping available resources of biogas
energy will enable the country to stabilize power supply. Wastes
used for biogas production has enormous potential for reduction
of environmental pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
