<HEADLINE> UN Concerned about Safety of its Staff in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations expressed
here today its "deep concern" over the safety of its staff in
Mazar-e-Sharif, northwest Afghanistan, following reports that they
have been threatened with "serious actions" by warring factions.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Special Mission to Afghanistan (UNSMA) is
deeply concerned about the safety and well-being of the U.N. and
Non-Governmental Organization staff in Mazar-e-Sharif, where the
Afghan Islamic Taliban militia and their northern rivals are
battling for the control of the city, UNSMA Head Norbert Holl said
here today in a press release.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. is engaged solely in a mediation process and in
humanitarian activities in Afghanistan and that any suggestion of
undercover activities is groundless," Holl said.
</P>
<P>
Holl appealed in the name of the Secretary General of the U.N.
to all the warring factions to facilitate the evacuation of the
U.N. and NGO staff from the city at the earliest possible time.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Hezb-e-Wahdat, one of the anti-Taliban
factions reportedly threatened today that unless the U.N. takes
action to stop Taliban jet raids on Mazar-e-Sharif, "serious
actions" will be taken against the U.N. staff in the city who he
said were passing on intelligence to the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and the International Red Cross had evacuated about 70
staff from Mazar-e-Sharif to Pakistan in late September. But due
to increased fighting in and around the city, the U.N. has failed
to bring the remaining staff in the city to safety.  
</P>
</TEXT>
