<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Main Construction of Tibet Museum Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The main construction of the Tibet
Museum, the first modern multi-function museum in the Tibetan history,
was completed here today.
</P>
<P>
A special ceremony was held today for the unveiling of the
museum's name, written by Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
In August 1995, the Chinese central government allocated over
100 million yuan for the construction of the museum in Lhasa,
capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the museum is the largest cultural project
Tibet has ever witnessed in this century.
</P>
<P>
The already-completed projects of the museum include a three-story
main exhibition hall and 30 warehouses, with a total area of
15,500 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The construction company said that both the hall and warehouses
feature up-to-date first-class security and firefighting equipment.
</P>
<P>
Museum Curator Chilai Qoigzha said that following the full
completion of its construction by the end of next year, the museum
would become a new symbol of Lhasa and a tourist attraction as
popular as the Potala Palace.
</P>
<P>
Yang Chuantang, vice-chairman of the Regional People's
Government, noted that the museum would also serve as a major base
for education on patriotism in Tibet, for it would contain many
relics and records that could prove Tibet has been an inalienable
part of China since ancient times.
</P>
<P>
He added that the museum would also display a number of
revolutionary relics from the past four decades and more, to
reflect the tremendous changes in the region since the complete
abolition of serfdom, especially since the beginning of China's
reform and opening-up to the outside.
</P>
<P>
"Let various rumors fabricated by western anti-China forces and
the Dalai clique declare their own intellectual bankruptcy in the
face of iron-clad proof," Yang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
