<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abacha Hails Nigeria's Macro-Economic Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state, General
Sani Abacha today hailed his government's success in bringing
macro-economic stability to the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is uplifting that as we come into the final year in office
of this administration, the nation is experiencing relative
macro-economic stability as a result of the policy measures and
actions we have taken," Abacha said in his early morning national
broadcast marking the west African country's 37th Independence
Day.
</P>
<P>
He noted the increased earnings from non-oil sector, stronger
foreign reserve, the favorable balance of payments, stricter
fiscal discipline and the reduced rate of inflation from 72.8
percent in December 1995 to 17.5 percent in June this year.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he said, the exchange rate of the Naira has
stabilized over the past four years. Interest rates have also
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's external debt stock has fallen to 28.06 billion U.S.
Dollars by the end of 1996 from 32 billion Dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
As to the oil sector which is backbone of the national
economy, Abacha said significant progress has been made in the
execution of four major natural gas utilization projects.
</P>
<P>
As order and security returns to the country, foreign and
local oil firms have maintained a high level of investment. As a
result, he declared that Nigeria's crude oil reserve has risen
from 20.8 billion barrels in 1994 to about 25 billion barrels
today.
</P>
<P>
He promised continued commitment to the Petroleum Trust Fund
which he established in 1994 and assured that the fund will
continue to give support to road, health, water supply, education
and other aspects of life with money from the oil sector.
</P>
<P>
He condemned the criminal acts of petroleum products smuggling
and the sabotage of oil production facilities, saying that the
government is committed to the uninterrupted supply of petroleum
products at affordable prices to the people.
</P>
<P>
In the agriculture sector, the head of state promised to make
government funds available to the millions of small-scale farmers
and to crack down on corruptions involved in fertilizer
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Abacha assured the government is making efforts
to boost the dwindling purchasing power of the Nigerian people,
especially those in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that a pay rise might come soon for the country's
civil servants, as the government has almost concluded a review
of their salaries and allowances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
