<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Sees Strong GDP Growth in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Canadian economy surged in July,
erasing concerns of a slowdown signaled by flat numbers in June,
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada reported Tuesday that the country's gross
domestic product (GDP) grew by 0.8 percent in July, doubling the pace
of growth forecasters had been expecting.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the economy has expanded at an annual rate above
three percent, almost twice the growth rate of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The July surge was partly influenced by recovery from production
disruptions in June in the auto, oil, mining and metal processing
industries.
</P>
<P>
Yet, growth in July was widely spread through the economy. There
was growth in 19 of the 21 manufacturing groups.
</P>
<P>
The strong GDP growth in July will prompt revisions of growth
estimated by many economics departments, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Paul Ferley, assistant chief economist at Bank of Montreal,
predicted a growth rate of 4.4-5 percent for the third quarter, up
from a previous forecast of 3.75-4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The strong growth data pushed the Canadian dollar higher yesterday
as speculation intensified that the Bank of Canada will raise its
benchmark rate soon.
</P>
<P>
The next major market-sensitive report will be the September labor
force survey results due October 10.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to watch out for a rate hike if growth in
employment pushes the jobless rate below nine percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
