<HEADLINE> Sion Protests Spartak Goal Was Too Small </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Swiss champion Sion has made a
formal protest to European soccer's ruling body that one of the
goals was too small for their UEFA Cup match away to Spartak
Moscow on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sion has asked that the first-round second-leg match, which
ended 2-2 but with Spartak winning 3-2 on aggregate, be awarded to
the Swiss side 3-0, allowing them to go through to the second
round.
</P>
<P>
Spartak angrily dismissed the complaint as frivolous but said
the club was not unduly concerned by the appeal.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, measurements by a UEFA match
delegate, which delayed the start of the game by 30 minutes, found
the crossbar on one of the goals at Moscow's Locomotiv stadium was
14 centimeters below the regulation height of 2.44 meters.
</P>
<P>
UEFA confirmed on Wednesday it had received the protest and
would make a decision before the second- round draw in Geneva on
Friday. 
</P>
