<HEADLINE> Zambia Sells Two Copper Mines to Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia signed the final
agreements here Tuesday for the sale of Luanshya and Chibuluma
Mines to two foreign companies as part of the privatization of
its copper mines.
</P>
<P>
The Post Today quoted Chairman of the Zambia consolidated
Copper Mines (ZCCM) Luke Mwananshiku as saying at the hand-over
ceremony that the sales are "an indication that the policy of
government regarding the privatization of ZCCM remains
unchanged."
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper also quoted Mines Minister Christon Tembo
as saying at the signing ceremony that the sale of the two mines
respectively to Binani Group of India and the Metorex Consortium
of South Africa are significant.
</P>
<P>
The two mines employ 7,000 people and produce over 50,000 tons
of finished copper and about 1,000 tons of finished cobalt
annually.
</P>
<P>
The two companies will invest a total of 103 million U.S.
Dollars in the two old mines within the next five years while a
new mine will be opened in Chibuluma south, according to Times of
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Tembo said his country will earn 150 million Dollars a year
when capital is pumped into the two mines and this will help
revamp the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The Banani Group have also pledged to re-equip the Luanshya
smelter and to introduce new technology to reduce pollution from
smelter gases. 
</P>
