<HEADLINE> Hamas Founder Released by Israel, Arrives in Amman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Shiekh Ahmed Yassin, the founder
of the Islamic Resistance Movement, Hamas, arrived here early this
morning after Israel released the seriously ailing anti-Israeli
hardliner from jail on Jordanian King Hussein's demand.
</P>
<P>
Hussein and Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali
received the spiritual leader at the airport, who was removed
from a Jordanian helicopter on a stretcher and later hospitalized
in the King Hussein Medical Center (KHMC) under Hussein's
instruction, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The king said today that he is happy to see that Israel
released Yassin only hours after he announced such a demand
Tuesday during a speech in Zarqa City, southwest of Amman.
</P>
<P>
Hussein expressed the hope that the release of Yassin would be
the first step of a series of Israeli actions that might help
reactivate the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The king later went to KHMC and visited Yassin, who had been
jailed by Israel in 1989 and expected to serve a life sentence for
ordering attacks by Hamas guerrillas against Israeli targets.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat also called repeatedly on
Israel to release Yassin, but his demands were just ignored.
</P>
<P>
Israel released the Hamas leader to exchange for two Canadian
tourists, who were arrested in Jordan for attacking Hamas leader
Khaled Mashal. Hamas claimed that the two foreigners are Israeli
agents in an assassination attempt on Mashal.
</P>
<P>
In the same hospital, Hussein also visited Mashal, head of the
political bureau of Hamas who is recovering from the September 25
attack.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was established in 1987 to fight against Israel's
occupation of Palestine. Most Hamas political bureau members live
in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and is now one
of the only two Arab countries that have peace with the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
