<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO to Help Malawi Secure Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) will launch a special food security pilot
program in Malawi next month to help the country secure a base of
food production by controlling water.
</P>
<P>
FAO director general Jacques Diouf, who visited Malawi
recently, said the country is lucky to be endowed with abundant
water resources like Lake Malawi, and it should not have its
people sleeping on empty stomachs for most of the year.
</P>
<P>
To irrigate crops and turn around the sad hunger story which
afflicts 60 percent of the population of 12 million, he said
Malawi should tap its good surface water, comprising a network of
rivers and lakes covering 20 percent of the country.
</P>
<P>
Only eight percent of Africa's arable land has water control
while the rest depends on the vagaries of climate, he said.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the water control is in five countries of
Egypt, Sudan, Morocco, Madagascar and South Africa, according to
him.
</P>
<P>
The biggest problem in Africa is water and the continent loses
four billion cubic meters of water to the sea every year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Diouf urged Africans to control that water as everybody else
does around the world and use it for irrigation.
</P>
<P>
FAO will provide start-up funds of 500,000 U.S. Dollars to
launch the program and this will be supplemented with bilateral
funds from the World Bank and the African Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
Malawi has only 10,000 hectares of the potential 200,000
hectares of land under irrigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0075 </DOCNO>
