<HEADLINE> Japan Warns of Fake Car Dealers in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese Ministry of
International Trade and Industry (MITI) has warned through the
Japanese embassy here that some Japanese car dealers might be
cheating their customers.
</P>
<P>
MITI, which was requested by the Japanese government to carry
out investigations into allegations by Zambian buyers that they
have not received their vehicles even after paying for them,
concluded that nothing could be done about the missing dealers
because the transactions did not have signed contracts.
</P>
<P>
"Under the given situation MITI considers that what the buyers
can now do is only to wait for the sellers' goodwill to keep the
promises," it said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the embassy said Tuesday that sometimes
vehicles take a long time to reach their destinations after being
ordered because sellers embarked upon the search for a particular
vehicle after the order.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes the dealers could deliberately keep the vehicles
until they have enough orders to reduce on freight costs, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that to avoid similar problems in future, MITI will
first investigate an organization selling cars and the government
will order that the vehicle be delivered.
</P>
<P>
In the case of a Mail Order Business, MITI will instruct the
sellers based on the laws of Japan to specify the time required
for delivery in the seller's advertisement.
</P>
<P>
"It is considered that the main cause of the trouble is
attributed to the lack of an agreement between the buyer and the
seller, concerning the delivery period of a vehicle," the
spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
