<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Living Buddhas" Helping Tibetan Blind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Doje, a 73-year-old Tibetan with
cataracts, realized his dream of regaining his eyesight after a
surgery arranged by the '97 Eyesight Restore Action.
</P>
<P>
"I never thought I would recover at such an old age," Doje said
with emotion. "I owe this to the generosity of the doctors -- they
are living Buddhas from Beijing."
</P>
<P>
The '97 Eyesight Restore Action, organized by the Red Cross
Society of China (RCSC), plans to perform eye surgeries for more
than 600 patients suffering from cataracts in Tibet within a
one-month period.
</P>
<P>
Since September 18, two medical teams have gone to a number of
Tibetan counties, including Nagarze, Gongbo'gyamba, Bomi, Zayu and
Lhunze, where intensive ultraviolet rays have brought on a high
incidence of cataracts.
</P>
<P>
Doje comes from Nagarze County, near Yamzho Yumco Lake, which
has one of the harshest natural environments in the Tibetan
Autonomous Region. A total of 151 patients with cataracts from
Nagarze County had undergo surgery at the Nagarze County Hospital
by last Monday. And on September 29, the medical team from the
Beijing Tongren Hospital, with help from the local medical staff,
operated non-stop from 8 a.m. till 11 p.m., and Chief surgeon Zhou
Jun performed eight surgeries without a break.
</P>
<P>
"I have never done so many operations continuously under such
difficult conditions. Frankly speaking, I am tired. But I can't
stop working with so many patients still waiting in the operating
room," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
The medical staff is working very hard to overcome difficulties
arisen from the poor-quality medical equipment and the unfamiliar
high-altitude environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos, Suharto Agree to Fight Currency Speculators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
and Indonesian President Suharto have agreed to forge a common
front to fight the speculative attacks on Southeast Asian
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said in his weekly press conference today that they made
the commitment in a phone conversation Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said his discussion with Suharto dealt on the need for a
united action to protect the rupiah, peso and other regional
currencies from further depreciation which has affected the growth
of the economies of the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
One specific mechanism, Ramos said, was the establishment of an
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) Fund to "weather"
the financial crisis sweeping the region and stabilize regional
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN finance ministers and monetary authorities have been
meeting in the past few months to discuss the current economic
situation in the region as well as the need for united action
against speculative currency attacks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said it was possible that central banks of all ASEAN
member-countries would adopt and implement common policies and
mechanisms to stabilize the region's currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
