<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abacha Reiterates Military's Quit in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state General
Sani Abacha reiterated today that the military administration
will hand over to an elected government a year later as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The political transition program drafted two years ago has
been "steadfastly implemented and "will by the grace of God
terminate on October 1, 1998 with the entry into office of an
elected civilian administration", according to Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The military ruler made the remarks in a 50-minute
pre-recorded speech on the national television station this
morning to mark the 37th anniversary of the country's
independence.
</P>
<P>
The transition to civil rule program proposed by the Abacha
regime, seen as a road to democracy in the country, has attracted
immense attention both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
But Abacha warned: "the success of any experiment of political
engineering ultimately depends on the watchfulness and commitment
of the people."
</P>
<P>
"For our political structures to work, we all must imbibe the
spirit of give and take, fair play, justice and respect of the
rule of law," he added.
</P>
<P>
The head of state felt "happily" satisfied that the
overwhelming majority of the Nigeria people and their leaders are
participating enthusiastically in the implementation of the
transition program.
</P>
<P>
With all restrictions on political activities lifted and the
five registered political parties firmly established and ready to
participate in the remaining elections of the transition period,
Abacha said, "the spirit and letter of the first stage of the
transition program have been successfully fulfilled."
</P>
<P>
There is one year to go to complete the transition program and
Nigerians have to elect state governors and a president during
the period. Preparations have been underway with the National
Electoral Commission of Nigeria in charge.
</P>
<P>
Despite Abacha's confidence in the transition program, his
speech today did not seem to allay speculations that he would
succeed himself by that time.
</P>
<P>
Whether Abacha will quit the military and run for the
presidency as a civilian has been a hot topic among Nigerians
since early this year.
</P>
<P>
Organizations for and against Abacha's participation in the
presidential election have been founded in the country. The
Nigerian army declared last week it will give full support to any
person elected as president, including Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year Abacha said it would depend on his
constituency if he would run for the presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
