<HEADLINE> Feature: A Day of Pride  (by Xu Xingtang) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- "We are proud of being
Chinese. We are especially happy to celebrate our own National Day
for the first time," said Lei Kuok-kun, a bus driver who led his
five-year-old son to the seaside promenade at the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center early this morning to pay their
salute to the hoisting of the national flag.
</P>
<P>
The solemn flag-raising ceremony held at 8:00 am today to mark
the 48th Chinese National Day was joined by over 3,000 local
residents, who were experiencing the first official flag-raising
ceremony in the Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
After watching the ceremony, a Mr. He, in his 60s, and his wife
had a picture taken in front of the flag post as a memento.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad to see the raising of our national flag," He said.
"You can see that Hong Kong has been doing well since it became an
SAR and we are very confident in our future."
</P>
<P>
The hoisting of the flag opened a wide range of official and
social activities throughout Hong Kong in celebration of the
National Day, which include a Formation Flypast with six aircraft,
a grand National Day reception held by the SAR government, and a
half-hour splendid fireworks display in the night.
</P>
<P>
To Hong Kong people, October 1 means much more than two days
off. After more than 150 years of British colonial rule, Hong Kong
residents are now able to celebrate the National Day of their
motherland.
</P>
<P>
Today's local newspapers devoted pages to the National Day,
hailing the achievements of the motherland and the successful
implementation of "one country, two systems" in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Walking through Hong Kong's downtown or residential areas,
people are greeted with a sea of five-star red flags and colored
banners. The economic prosperity and social stability that have
been maintained in Hong Kong since July 1 have clearly added
happiness to the festival.
</P>
<P>
The venue of the flag-raising ceremony -- Hong Kong Convention
and Exhibition Center -- itself is a pride of Hong Kong, in which
the handover ceremony at midnight June 30, as well as the most
recent World Bank/IMF Annual Meetings, were successfully held.
</P>
<P>
"We in Hong Kong take tremendous pride in our Chinese identity.
This is our home and we will move forward together to promote
prosperity of our country and the SAR," said Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of HKSAR, in his National Day message.
</P>
<P>
The latest official public opinion survey has revealed that 80
percent of Hong Kong people were confident that Hong Kong would
continue to be prosperous and stable, which is eight percentage
points higher than a similar survey conducted in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
