<HEADLINE> Abacha Vows to Save Troubled Education Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria head of state, General
Sani Abacha today vowed to save the country's education sector
from many years of bad planning and shortsightedness.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at his early morning national broadcast
marking the country's 37th anniversary of independence.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigeria's education sector has been troubled
by the severe strain and stress occasioned by many years of bad
planning and shortsightedness and was worse hit by a sliding
economy.
</P>
<P>
"With recent improvement in our national finance we shall soon
be in a position to deploy even more sources to the
rehabilitation of this crucial sector of our national growth and
development," said the head of state.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in the past one year, relative stability and
sanity have been restored in Nigerian schools, and that for the
first time in many years, schools began and concluded an academic
session without disruptions occasioned by strikes, closures or
student unrest.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that a 25-man committee set up by his government
to examine the problems of the education sector will soon submit
its final report.
</P>
<P>
The head of state expressed the hope that the findings and
recommendations of the group will greatly assist the government
in evolving further measures to revamp the education sector.
</P>
<P>
Another source of hope for the sector, he said, is the
Education Tax Fund established through a decree in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The fund has so far collected about seven billion Naira (about
86 million U.S. Dollars) which will be soon distributed to all
kinds of educational institutions, said the head of state.
</P>
<P>
According to him, 40 percent of the fund will go to primary
schools, 25 percent to universities, 12.5 percent to
polytechnics, 12.5 percent to colleges and the rest 10 percent to
secondary schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
