<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Thailand Open Third Common Border Crossing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Thailand today
opened along their common border the third crossing point, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The river crossing checkpoint links Bukit Bunga in Malaysia's
northeastern state of Kelantan and Bukit Tar in Thailand's Weng
District, and will open at 6 am and close at 7 pm daily, the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
Commuters have to take the boat to cross the 20-metre wide
Sungai Jenub which separates the border.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the river crossing, as a reflection of close
bilateral ties between the two countries, would provide easy
movement of people of the two sides and enhance business
activities in the area, the news agency said quoting Immigration
Director-General Mohamed Zakri Abdul Rashid.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, it will also help overcome the problem of illegal
entry by villagers in the border areas" who have relatives in the
other side of the border, the Malaysian official was quoted as
saying after visiting the area.
</P>
<P>
The official said a complex would be set up in the area as soon
as Malaysia and Thailand officially agreed to the building of a
bridge across the river to replace the temporary building which at
present houses the Immigration, the Royal Customs and Excises
Departments.
</P>
<P>
The other two checkpoints at the Kelantan-Thailand border are
in Rantau Panjang where a bridge has been built over border river
Sungai Golok, which opens from 6 am to 10 pm daily, and at
Pengkalan Kubur, Tumpat, which opens daily from 6 am to 7 pm,
according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The new checkpoint would make it more convenient for people
from both countries to cross over from other side.  
</P>
</TEXT>
