<HEADLINE> Belarus to Release Russian Journalist Within Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko said today that the head of the Minsk bureau of Russian
Public Television (ORT) Pavel Sheremet, who has been detained in
Grodno, will be released within two or three days.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko told reporters in Minsk that Sheremet is "not a
threat to society," and it does not make sense to keep him under
arrest since the investigation has been completed, Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
Prior to a court procedure, Sheremet can be released in
exchange for a written pledge not to leave the region, Lukashenko
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision to release Sheremet is exclusively within the
jurisdiction of the Belarussian law enforcement bodies, adding the
release became possible "only after the investigation conducted in
strict compliance with the procedural norms had been completed."
</P>
<P>
Sheremet and another ORT employee Dmitry Zavadsky were charged
by Belarus with "illegally and repeatedly crossing the state
(Belarrussian-Lithuanian) border."
</P>
<P>
Sheremet has been under detention since July; Zavadsky was
released earlier. 
