<HEADLINE> NATO Defense Ministers to Discuss Bosnian Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAASTRICHT, Netherlands, October 1 (Xinhua) -- NATO defense
ministers will hold a two-day talk on when and how to phase out
the presence in Bosnia-Herzegovina of SFOR troops whose
peacekeeping mandate expires in June, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In their annual informal meeting prior to the policy-making
conference scheduled for December, the defense ministers will be
briefed on the latest developments following municipal elections,
which were held on September 13-14, and exchange views on setting
up a security framework in Bosnia for the remaining nine months of
the SFOR (NATO-led Multinational Stabilization Force).
</P>
<P>
NATO reinforced its ground force to 40,000 troops before the
municipal elections and it intends to keep the troops in Bosnia
to ensure that parliamentary elections occur without incident on
October 23, reliable sources said.
</P>
<P>
Both elections are hailed as important steps toward
implementing the Dayton peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Though no decision will be made during the meeting in this
Dutch town, the defense ministers will try to figure out whether
to postpone or simply skip the planned third phase of the
peacekeeping operation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR had planned to reduce its troops after the municipal
elections. But conditions for a planned phase-out seemed premature
after Bosnian Serb loyalists, faithful to war-time leader Radovan
Karadzic, and the local media incited unrest against the presence
of the international community prior to the elections . 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
