<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Be On for New Friends, Says Abacha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has successfully made new
friends with other countries in recent years despite the
hostilities from a section of the international community, the
head of state General Sani Abacha announced today.
</P>
<P>
Deliberating the country's foreign policy in a speech to mark
the 37th anniversary of independence, Abacha said that his
military administration was "satisfied with the remarkable level
of response we have received" in looking to "other parts of the
world to make new friends".
</P>
<P>
The former British colony's traditional allies in Europe and
America imposed sanctions on the country in 1993 when the then
military regime annulled that year's presidential election on
charges of malpractices.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth suspended Nigeria's membership following the
execution of nine tribal activists in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
All this has seriously hampered the development of Nigeria and
the government has to turn to other parts of the world,
particularly the east, for new friends.
</P>
<P>
The country has fostered good relations with some Asian
countries, including Malaysia, China and the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea, in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Thus Abacha declared: "Despite attempts by some misguided
persons, and assisted by a hostile section of the international
community to wage an ill-motivated campaign against our country,
we are satisfied that Nigeria's international stature has
remained undiminished."
</P>
<P>
For the country's bid to look for new friends which "became
necessary for Nigeria," Abacha explained, "this seems to be
normal practice by all nations and our country should be an
exception."
</P>
<P>
He noted: "we are conscious of the fact that true friendship
can only be nurtured on the matrix of mutual understanding, trust
and respect."
</P>
<P>
He further stated that Nigeria will remain open to all those
who wish to be friends and cooperate with the country.
</P>
<P>
The head of state also hoped the Commonwealth leadership to
embrace fair play, genuine dialogue and negotiations in order to
resolve the unfortunate impasse between the organization and
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Abacha seemed particularly satisfied with the "traditionally
constructive roles" Nigeria has continued to play "within our
sub-region, within Africa and indeed on the larger international
arena".
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the active role Nigeria plays in the
sub-regional organization of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS), of which Nigeria takes the chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
Under ECOWAS, Nigeria has led the peace-keeping operations in
Liberia with huge human, financial and materials contribution,
which resulted in an end of the country's seven-year-old civil
war and a successful establishment of an elected civilian
government.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now is also actively involved in the resolution of the
crisis in Sierra Leone, where a number of officers overthrew the
legitimate government in a coup on May 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
With the success in Liberia, Abacha said, "we already have
experience which we will bring to bear in our search for a
peaceful resolution of the crisis."
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS chairman called on Sierra Leone's military junta to
resume serious negotiations and dialogue for the early
reinstatement of ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, the return
of peace and security and the settlement of refugees and the
displaced.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the international community to give support to
ECOWAS effort to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS decided in August to impose economic embargo on Sierra
Leone in order to force the junta to step down. The embargo has
since been enforced by the west African peace-keeping force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
