<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997 Right Livelihood Award Shared by Five Individuals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 1 (Xinhua)--The 1997 Right Livelihood Awards
will be shared by five outstanding individuals from three
continents "for their contributions to a sustainable future for
humanity," the Right Livelihood Award Foundation said here today.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Ki-Zerbo, a historian from Burkina Faso is honored
"for a lifetime of scholarship and activism that has laid out the
history of Black Africa and identified the key principles and
processes by which Africans can create a better future."
</P>
<P>
The Right Livelihood Foundation praised Mycle Schneider from
France and Jinzaburo Takagi from Japan for their "struggle to rid
humanity of the threat posed by the manufacture, transport, use
and disposal of plutonium."
</P>
<P>
German scientist Michael Succow won the award for his
"exemplary commitment to safeguard important ecosystems and areas
of outstanding natural value for future generations."
</P>
<P>
American lady Cindy Duehring was honored "for her
extraordinary courage and determination to put her personal
tragedy at the service of humanity by generating the knowledge
that can help others understand and combat the risks that toxic
chemicals present to human life and health."
</P>
<P>
The five outstanding individuals will share this year's Award
of 240,000 U.S. dollars. The Awards, regarded as the "Alternative
Nobel Prize," were introduced in 1980 "to honor and support those
offering practical and exemplary answers to the most urgent
challenges facing mankind today."
</P>
<P>
The idea and original funding for the award came from Jakob von
Uexkull, a Swedish-German writer and philatelist. It is
now funded by endowment income as well as donations from
individuals all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The awards will be presented at a ceremony in the Swedish
Parliament on December 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
