<HEADLINE> Thailand to Clean up House for Tourism Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Tourism Authority of
Thailand (TAT) will need to "clean up" the country and improve its
image so as to attract more foreign tourists over the next two
years, according to Deputy Prime Minister Thaksin Shinawatra.
</P>
<P>
TAT is seeking cooperation from other government agencies to
deal with the country's negative image and to solve such problems
as crime, local mafias, traffic and airport security, that hurt
the tourism industry, according to the Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry, which controls the police department,
will play a significant role in the task, Thaksin said.
</P>
<P>
TAT is set to launch a two-year "amazing Thailand" campaign for
1998 and 1999 at the end of this year, aimed at attracting a total
of 17 million foreign tourists with a total earning of 600 billion
baht (16.7 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
During the past two years, there were about 7 million foreign
arrivals and tourism-related income of about 200 billion baht (8.5
billion dollars) each year.  
</P>
