<HEADLINE> Russia Joins SFOR Action Against Serb Transmitters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAASTRICHT, Netherlands, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia, that had
lashed out at the NATO for not consulting it before taking some
Pale-held transmission towers, today took part in an SFOR action of
taking four of the Srpska Radio and Television (SRT) transmitters.
</P>
<P>
The NATO-led SFOR troops captured the four transmission towers in
Bosnia at the request of the high representative of the international
community.
</P>
<P>
High Representative Carlos Westendorp requested SFOR military
action earlier today after he determined that the SRT had violated the
Udrigovo Agreement of September 2 by their unacceptable treatment of a
September 26 press conference by Justice Arbour.
</P>
<P>
The SRT television tampered with the tape recording of the press
conference before airing the program.
</P>
<P>
Russian SFOR troops set up road blocks to help prevent provocative
incidents from local Serbs who had blocked SFOR maneuvres several
times prior to Bosnia's municipal elections held on September 13 and
14.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 SFOR troops took the four transmitters without incident,
according to NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, and they will be
handed over to new management, which the NATO chief defined as the
parties supporting the Republika Srpska president in Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
The aim of SFOR's action is to assist the international high
representative in ensuring that the media in the Republika Srpska
reflects international norms of professional media conduct and fully
supports the goals of the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief described the SFOR action earlier today as a
demonstration of NATO's determination to back those who support
Dayton and to react swiftly and robustly against those who seek to
obstruct the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the Bosnian municipal elections, the SFOR troops had
captured a couple of radio and television transmission towers in
Bosnia. They later returned them to loyalists to Serb war-time leader
Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
Pro-Karadzic media in Bosnia was blamed by NATO and other
international organizations as inciting unrest against international
presence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
