<HEADLINE> Australians Water Bombing Planes to Combat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian water bombing planes
will be sent to Indonesia to fight the country's disastrous forest
fires which have blanketed much of South-East Asia in a thick
haze, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said today.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to announce an additional Australian commitment
of up to one million Australian dollars (720,000 U.S. dollars) for
aerial water bombing to assist Indonesia to tackle emergency
problems resulting from the forest fires," Downer said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The announcement comes just two days after Mr. Downer committed
another one million Australian dollars in emergency assistance to
deal with the health problems caused by the fires.
</P>
<P>
The fires are reportedly unlikely to be extinguished until the
onset of the monsoon rains, which are unusually late this year.
</P>
<P>
But Downer said the Australian aircraft would help prevent the
crisis worsening.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said the water bombing aircraft should be
able to go quickly into action.
</P>
<P>
"The lead members of the Water Bombing and other Fire
Management and the Health Assistance teams are scheduled to arrive
in Indonesia by the end of the week."
</P>
<P>
Australia would send two fixed-wing aircraft to Indonesia
within five days, both capable of carrying 3,000 litters of water.
</P>
<P>
