<HEADLINE> Gold Stocks Lead Australian Share Market Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Rallying gold stocks pushed the
Australian share market higher today, with the gold sector's
performance lifting miners generally.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index improved 12.3 points to 2779.2, with
the all resources index up 14.7 points to 1376.9 and the all
industrials up 10.7 points to 4562.5.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said industrials were mixed, with a late rally by banks
as international volume buyers came in to the market and
institutions repositioned at the start of a new quarter.
</P>
<P>
"Gold was the highlight of the day and the leading stocks
showed very good gains," Bill Richmond from Peake Lands Kirwan
said.
</P>
<P>
The gold index improved 4.5 per cent today after the gold
bullion price improved from last night's close of 328.10 U.S.
dollars per ounce to close at 334.70 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index gained 58.9 points to 1357.2.
</P>
<P>
Australia's biggest gold house Normandy jumped ten cents to
1.85 Australian dollars and Acacia leapt 17 cents to 1.86
Australian dollars on heavy turnover while Lihir was 15 cents
better at 2.30 Australian dollars and Plutonic finished 27 cents
higher at 4.06 Australian dollars. Newcrest added ten to 2.58
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
While gold prices rose, zinc and nickel prices fell overnight,
but resources stocks generally improved.
</P>
<P>
Bellwether BHP improved seven cents to 16.15 Australian
dollars, Rio Tinto was 23 cents higher at 20.98 Australian dollars
while WMC was a significant improver, finishing 16 cents better at
6.64 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among industrials, News Corp ordinary shares fell 7.7 cents to
7.00 Australian dollars on turnover of 5.8 million shares but the
preferred shares rose eight cents to 6.19 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Banks recovered late today after early selling, with Westpac
down seven cents to 8.63 Australian dollars, off a low of 8.53
Australian dollars, and ANZ steady at 11.28 Australian dollars,
off a low of 11.12 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National Australia and Commonwealth banks both fell seven cents
to 21.15 Australian dollars and 16.97 Australian dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for the day was 414.2 million shares at a
value of 698.4 million US dollars, with rises outnumbering falls
675 to 560.  
</P>
