<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Exports Up in First Nine Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's export turnover reached
6.4 billion U.S.dollars in the first nine months, accounting for
72 percent of its yearly target, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The figure, 23.4 percent higher than that of the same period
last year, was the result of an increase from 12.9 percent to 79
percent in the export of coffee, rice, rubber, crude oil, seafood
and footwear.
</P>
<P>
The export of farm, forest products and seafood alone amounted
to 2.736 billion dollars, a year-to-year increase of 21.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country is making more efforts to reach the planned export
value of 9.2 billion dollars for 1997, or 930 million dollars for
each remaining month of the year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports dropped to 8.22 billion dollars in the first
nine months of the year, a decrease of 2.1 percent or 180 million
dollars over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The import of fuel, machinery and equipment saw an increase of
7.7 percent over the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country's foreign trade deficit decreased by
56.5 percent or 1.395 billion dollars in the first nine months.
</P>
</TEXT>
