<HEADLINE> Thailand's Shrimp Production to Drop This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's shrimp production
this year is expected to decrease by 35,000 tons because of
several adverse factors, according to Charoen Pokphand Group (CP),
the country's leading agro-business group.
</P>
<P>
The country's shrimp output this year will reach 170,000 tons,
as against 205,000 tons in 1996, according to the Bangkok Post
today, quoting a CP source.
</P>
<P>
Recent floods in the south have caused serious damage to shrimp
farms and the El Nino phenomenon is causing higher sea water
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
White spot disease has wiped out many hatcheries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, as a result of the depreciation of the baht,
shrimp feed price has increased 8,6 percent, bringing about higher
production coast.  
</P>
