<HEADLINE> Discarded Batteries Reclaimed in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital of Beijing
is now promoting a campaign to reclaim worn-out batteries for
recycling, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Special boxes bearing slogans like "You want a beautiful
environment, I want your batteries" will be set up along streets
and in stores later this year for the collection of discarded
batteries.
</P>
<P>
Sponsors of this campaign include the Beijing Television
Station, the municipality's Regenerated Resources Multi-Purpose
Use Office and the China Environmental Protection Fund (CEPF).
</P>
<P>
"Unreclaimed worn out batteries, which contain harmful metals,
are a serious source of pollution," Wang Qunsheng, a manager of a
local electric equipment company, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yiling, an expert with the CEPF, said that discarded
batteries release mercury, cadmium and lead, which are extremely
harmful to the human body.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, these released metals will seep into the
earth and pollute the soil and groundwater.
</P>
<P>
"The best way to guard against this pollution is to collect
these batteries and to reclaim the noxious metals," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Batteries are widely used for walkmans, radios and other kinds
of miniature electronic devices to the tune of nearly 10,000 tons
a year in Beijing alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0112 </DOCNO>
