<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haze Reaches Dangerous Level in Indonesia: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Haze raging through Sumatra and
Kalimantan islands in Indonesia has reached "dangerous levels",
Health Minister Sujudi said here last night.
</P>
<P>
"The haze can cause lung infection, particularly for children,"
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Forest and land fires have sent haze (smoke, ash and dust) with
260 particles per cubic meter, on a scale where 100 was considered
tolerable, sources at the Health Ministry today quoted the
minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
"In some areas the level has reached 2,000. This is endangering
people's health," Sujudi said, without referring to a specific
region.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had already dropped 400,000 masks around
the country and was suggesting the use of wet towels and
handkerchiefs to purify the contaminated air.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of expatriates were reportedly being evacuated from
Sumatra Tuesday amid fears the haze blanketing the region could
damage their health.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations Tuesday described bush fires in
Indonesia as an environmental emergency which would affect
individual health and the well being of Asian economies for years
to come.
</P>
<P>
UN experts, gathering in Jakarta to coordinate international
efforts to douse the flames, delivered the grim message that even
if the fires were controlled soon, the pollution after-effects
could last for years.
</P>
<P>
"The long-term effects are in economic, health, social and
ecological areas," said Ravi Rajan, the chief representative of
the UN In Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 hectares of land and forest in Sumatra and
Kalimantan were estimated to have been scorched by fires in the
last three months.
</P>
<P>
As the haze was worsening, seven most affected provinces of
Riau, Jambi and South Sumatra and East Kalimantan, West
Kalimantan, Central Kalimantan and South Kalimantan were declared
on first alert status.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
