<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa Urged to Prepare for El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries
have been urged by the World Bank to enhance regional cooperation
to prepare for the early appearance of El Nino, which could cause
a long spell of devastating drought in the region.
</P>
<P>
Regional cooperation is needed although, with better
forecasting technology, the region is now better prepared for the
early approach of El Nino, bank officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There are clearly benefits to integration in the region...
Africa is not even on the map for many investors as a trade area
and that is a concern," said Pamela Cox, World Bank Country
Director for South Africa, Botswana, Namibia, Lesotho and
Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are many cross-border issues in the region
such as water management, transport infrastructure for landlocked
nations, improving communications systems and addressing health
issues such as malaria.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank has identified broad targets for future
assistance, including encouraging trade links, developing
transport corridors, making capital flow easier and solving water
supply problems.
</P>
<P>
The South African Weather Bureau said it is detecting early
signs of the appearance of El Nino.
</P>
<P>
"The fairly good rains we experienced a few weeks ago,
followed by these very high temperatures (in the past few days),
is an indication of the disturbance in the weather patterns,"
said Mike Edwards, the bureau's deputy director.
</P>
<P>
Normally El Nino does not start causing weather problems in
South Africa before December, but it is known that the El Nino
pattern started early this year.
</P>
<P>
As an indication of the approach of El Nino, a strong heat
wave swept the country in the past few days when summer has
barely begun.
</P>
<P>
At least 13 heat records for September were broken with
temperatures as high as 42.6 being recorded on Monday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's hottest temperature in Kruger National Park in
Mpumalanga Province on Monday has been a record high in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
High temperatures were also recorded in the northern Cape and
Gauteng provinces.
</P>
<P>
"I would not say that this particular heat is an indication
that there is going to be a drought in South Africa... it is an
indication that there is already a disturbance in our weather
patterns," edwards said.
</P>
<P>
The Pretoria-based weather bureau predicted that hot to very
hot weather will continue in most of the country for the next two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's National Maize Producers' Association, worried
about an early onset of an El Nino drought in southern Africa,
has warned its members to delay planting this year. Early El
Nino could be disastrous in the region, it said.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino weather phenomenon, caused by the warming of
Pacific waters off South America, is already being blamed for
economic turmoil in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
In southeast Asia, a dry spell has savaged maize crops in
Java, Indonesia, and it is feared that the El Nino effect could
rival that in 1982-83, which cost the world about 13 billion
U.S.Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
