<HEADLINE> SFOR Captures Transmitters in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAASTRICHT, Netherlands, October 1 (Xinhua) -- NATO-led SFOR troops
today captured four radio and television transmission towers in Bosnia
at the request of the high representative of the international
community.
</P>
<P>
The news was announced by NATO Secretary General Javier Solana who
was attending the annual informal meeting of NATO defense ministers.
</P>
<P>
High Representative Carlos Westendorp requested SFOR military
action earlier today after he determined that the Srpska Radio and
Television (SRT) had violated the Udrigovo Agreement of September 2 by
their unacceptable treatment of a September 26 press conference by
Justice Arbour.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 SFOR troops took the four transmission towers without
incident, according to Solana, and they will be handed over to new
management, which the NATO chief defined as the parties supporting the
Republika Srpska president.
</P>
<P>
The aim of SFOR's action is to assist the international high
representative in ensuring that the media in the Republika Srpska
reflects international norms of professional media conduct and fully
supports the goals of the Dayton peace accord, Solana said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief described the SFOR action earlier today as a
demonstration of NATO's determination to back those who support
Dayton and to react swiftly and robustly against those who seek to
obstruct the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the Bosnian municipal elections held on September 13 and
14, the NATO-led SFOR troops had captured a couple of radio and
television transmission towers in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Local media loyal to Bosnian war-time leader Radovan Karadzic was
blamed by NATO and other international organizations as inciting
unrest against international presence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
