<HEADLINE> UNITA Headquarters to Shift to Luanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A high-level delegation of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) will
gather soon in Luanda to make arrangements for the shifting of
its headquarters to the capital, the Angola Catholic Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Horacio Junjunvili, UNITA's deputy chief in the Joint
Commission of the Angolan Peace Process, made the statement
Tuesday during an interview with the radio.
</P>
<P>
He said, the delegation led by UNITA General Secretary Correin
Victor will come to Luanda in a few days. However, Junjunvili
did not reveal any more details.
</P>
<P>
UNITA is the biggest opposition party and the second biggest
party in Angola. Although 70 of its parliament members have been
admitted to the National Assembly and those who joined the
national unity government have sworn in, UNITA
hasn't set up formal or legal institutions in Luanda since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Ever since November, 1994 when Angola's warring parties signed
the Lusaka Peace Accord and formally announced the end of the
civil war, the central leadership agency of the former rebel
movement has been located in Bailundo city in Angola's central
province of Huambo, and Andulo city in Bie province.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan leaders have reiterated for many times that the
shifting of UNITA's headquarters to Luanda means the victorious
ending of all work regarding the peace process. 
</P>
