<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kia Creditors Press for Kia's Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Creditors of South Korea's ailing
Kia group are pushing for a court receivership order for Kia,
which would declare the automotive group bankrupt and enable its
hand-over to a third party.
</P>
<P>
But the courts order to freeze debt obligations and assets of
Kia Information System on Tuesday, and the earlier orders to
freeze assets of nine Kia subsidiaries, have dampened creditors'
hope to call in debts immediately.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of 55 of Kia's creditors on Monday, the creditors
renewed their call for Kia Motors Corp., the flagship company of
the nation's eighth largest group, to file for court receivership
instead of court protection.
</P>
<P>
They said that court protection does not help at all for Kia's
normalization, as creditors could not provide additional funds to
Kia under the system.
</P>
<P>
The call came as workers of the Kia Motors Corp. started a
two-day strike Monday morning to protested creditors' pressure for
Kia's insolvency, demanding a court protection in order to allow
more time to save the debt-laden conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen of Kia's 15 affiliates had sought special court
protection against debt default by creditors or court receivership
last week. The spokesman of Kia said that the group was trying to
secure more time to get rid of the crisis of collapse under its
incumbent management system.
</P>
<P>
Court protection differs from court receivership in that it
allows the current management to keep managerial rights while
trying to save the group through self-rescue efforts and debt
rescheduling.
</P>
<P>
Kia ran into trouble after piling up debts totalling 9.5
trillion won (10.4 billion U.S. dollars) by the end of May. It was
placed under protection by its creditor banks on July 15 after
they determined that Kia would default on debt repayment.
</P>
<P>
Kia's trouble battered the Seoul stock market, pulling down the
broad-based composite stock price index by as much as 129.98
points or 17.2 percent over the past two and a half months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
