<HEADLINE> S.Korean Businesses Welcome Amnesty Tycoons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Major South Korean conglomerates and
their organizations welcomed the government's Tuesday decision to
amnesty 23 business tycoons sentenced for bribing former President Roh
Tae-woo.
</P>
<P>
"The special amnesty will clear smears on the image of the major
business leaders in the scandal," the Federation of Korean Industries
(FKI), a powerful lobbying group for giant conglomerates, said in a
statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The amnesty will also help reinvigorate the dampened morale of the
business circle, the federation added.
</P>
<P>
South Korean government Tuesday decided to grant special
pardons to the tycoons who were convicted of bribing, embezzling as
well as tax evading.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision was interpreted as a way to help revive
the nation's sagging economy by lifting the burden from the
businessmen, allowing them to concentrate on business activities.
</P>
<P>
After the exposure of the scandal related to the former president
Roh, the involved tycoons and their companies have been arguing that
not the companies but the circumstance under which they were
"compelled" to give money to the President and government officials
should be blamed.
</P>
<P>
Major conglomerates, involved in the scandal, which led to the
sentencing of Lee Kun-hee of the Samsung Group, Kim Woo-choong of the
Daewoo Group and other business magnates, have experienced
difficulties in their overseas operations, it said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the decision will contribute to the reviving of the
sagging domestic economy," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
