<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 08:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Security Forces on High Alert Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli security forces
remain on a high state of alert for possible terror attacks by
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) over the Jewish holiday
season, Israel radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of police and soldiers have been deployed in the
public places across the country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli security officials as saying that
despite the recent crackdown of terrorists by the Palestinian
National Authority (PA), in which more than 200 Hamas activists
were arrested, there are still terror cells operating in the West
Bank, which may plan further bombing attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Chief of General Staff Ammon Lipkin Shahak said
Tuesday that since the terror cell that carried out the Jerusalem
bombings was uncovered, the PNA has been making an extra effort to
fight terror, but this does not mean they are dismantling the
terror infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"We have heard the declaration. It has to be translated into
action that can be seen, not just in detaining (terrorists) but
everything that follows that detention," he said, citing the
judicial procedures and how long and under what conditions the
terrorists would be held in Palestinian prisons.
</P>
<P>
Shahak also noted that both the PNA and Hamas face a dilemma
following the exposure of the terror cell. Hamas is considering
whether or not to carry on with the terror attacks, while PA has
to decide whether or not to take action against Hamas, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a senior Israeli army official said Tuesday that
Israel has given the PNA a short list of terrorists considered to
be extremely dangerous, including Adel Awadallah who is believed
to have planned the two recent suicide bombings at Jerusalem's
Mahaneh Yehuda market and Ben Yehuda mall, which killed 25 people
and wounded hundreds.
</P>
<P>
Shahak stressed that Awadallah is still roaming the
countryside between Israeli and Palestinian controlled territory,
saying that "he is moving about, most of the time he is in area A
(under Palestinian control), but he is also in areas where we are
in control."
</P>
<P>
Rosh Hashana (Jewish New Year) will begin tonight and the
whole holiday season in Israel will last through the month.
</P>
</TEXT>
