<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: "Marcos Gold" Arouses Controversy in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
has branded as complete falsehood the allegation that proceeds
from the alleged sale of Marcos gold have been deposited in secret
Swiss bank accounts belonging to him.
</P>
<P>
"Well, I consider that a conspiracy of falsehood and
fabrications and that is what these news sources, whoever they
are, have been saying these past few days," Ramos told reporters
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Without naming the sources of the allegation, the president was
clearly referring to a story by American lawyer Rober Swift, who
represents the "human rights victims" (HRV) under Marcos' rule.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Manila-based reporters at a tele-conference in Los
Angeles Tuesday, Swift dragged the name of President Ramos into
the resuscitated controversy over the Marcos wealth stashed in
Swiss banks, the alleged discovery of 1,241 tons of Marcos gold
and the reported sale of several tons of it recently.
</P>
<P>
Swift claimed that President Ramos is maintaining an account in
the Swiss Bank Julius Baer &AMP; Co. ltd, where part of the Marcos
assets, mostly in gold amounting to 13 billion U.S. dollars, were
reportedly kept in coded accounts which he and other HRV lawyers
uncovered recently.
</P>
<P>
Swift said that a memo by retired Swiss Judge Peter Ritter, who
is in charge of a trust for some of the late President Ferdinand
Marcos' wealth, "suggested that no other than the President of the
Philippines, Fidel Ramos, has an account at Bank Julius Baer in
Switzerland."
</P>
<P>
Swift's allegation drew strong reactions in the Philippine
Parliament, ranging from threats of impeachment of President Ramos
to calls for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
Senator Miriam Santiago Tuesday urged President Ramos to resign
after his name was dragged into the fray. She said that other
administration officials involved in hiding the Marcos wealth
should be investigated for plundering what belongs to the Filipino
people.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to Swift's allegations and parliamentarians' pressure,
Ramos denied he has a bank deposit in Switzerland. He admitted
that he had a U.S. dollar account "many years ago which I closed
even before I became president on June 30, 1992."
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that efforts to link him to the Marcos wealth "might
be part of a conspiracy of some irresponsible and spurious or may
be criminally inclined people who are trying to bring upon the
Filipino audience such convoluted statements."
</P>
<P>
Imelda, widow of late president Marcos also denied that the
president, other government officials and her son Ferdinand Marcos
Jr. were involved in the alleged withdrawal of their assets from
Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to check possible public anger caused by the
allegation, Philippine Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson
issued a statement here Tuesday, saying recent reports that Marcos
was able to spirit away from the Philippines a gold hoard totaling
1,241 tons are incredible.
</P>
<P>
Marcos, who ruled the Philippines for 20 years, moved to
Hawaii, a U.S. state, after he was forced out of office in
February 1986 and died in 1989. He was accused of spiriting
billions of dollars, and hundreds of tons of gold from the state
coffer.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that the total gold production in the Philippines
over the 20 year period from 1977 (when gold refinery operation
started in the Philippines) to August 31, 1997 was estimated at
636 tons.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, of this total production, the central bank
was able to purchase only 286 tons with the balance of gold
production being directly exported by private gold producers.
</P>
<P>
By the annual averages, it would take the central bank "the
last 87 years just to amass the gold for the so-called Marcos
hoard," the governor said.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports today, the Ramos
administration threatened to file a civil suit for damages against
American Lawyer Swift and retired Swiss Judge Ritter for their
allegations.
</P>
<P>
But analysts here warned said that as the alleged Marcos gold
hoard is a very complicated issue, it is hard to predict if it
would lead to a political crisis in the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Official Slams Israel's Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amir
Moussa has said that Israel's settlement policy "humiliates" the
Palestinians and he has "no confidence" in Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's handling of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published on the Jerusalem Post daily today, he
criticized Netanyahu's announcement last week build another 300
Jewish housing units in Efrat near Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He said this move is prohibited under international law, and
goes against not only the Oslo accords, but also the
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"So I believe that the position taken by the Israeli
government is totally illegal and false," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa sharply criticized some Jewish settlers' taking-over
last month of the houses in East Jerusalem's Ras Al-Amud, a
densely populated Arab area.
</P>
<P>
The mere presence of all those people in this neighborhood is a
violation of the letter and spirit of whatever agreement concluded
between Israel and the Palestinians, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that he does not believe that Netanyahu really
wants a "fair" solution with the Palestinians because every
couple of days he announces something in order to poison
the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
To reopen the peace talks, he said, the major responsibility
lies on the shoulder of Netanyahu, not on Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat's.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Netanyahu's proposal to place the final-status
issues on the fast track negotiations with the PNA, Moussa said
Netanyahu even did not cooperate on the transitional issues such
as Israeli troops redeployment in West Bank and he could not
believe that Netanyahu would be ready to negotiate with the PNA on
such final-status issues as Jerusalem and Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Israeli government to take actual actions towards
the reopening of the Middle East peace process, not only
making promises.
</P>
<P>
He said if the Israeli government does not change its
current hardline policy towards the peace talks, the failure
of the scheduled regional economic summit in Qatar this November
is assured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
