<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G15 Summit to Be Held in Malaysia Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The annual summit of the
Group of 15 developing countries or G15 will be held in Malaysia
on November 3-5.
</P>
<P>
Kenya will be admitted as the 16th member at the forthcoming
summit but the name of the grouping will remain unchanged,
Malaysian Foreign Ministry's Secretary-General Abdul Kadir Mohamad
told reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said the summit had already achieved its
quorum with the confirmed attendance of eight heads of state or
government and a vice president whose names would be made known
later due to security considerations.
</P>
<P>
On the commitment of member countries in view of the difficulty
in getting a quorum for the past summits and proposals to space
out the summit instead of holding it annually, Abdul Kadir said
the G15 was still important as it was the only forum for
developing countries to come together for their mutual benefit
apart from undertaking joint development projects.
</P>
<P>
He said that as for the frequency of the summit, the leaders
would decide at the forthcoming summit here whether to maintain
the existing yearly format or otherwise and added that Malaysia
was flexible on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The summit would be preceded by a meeting of economic ministers
of the group for the first time, Abdul Kadir said.
</P>
<P>
The economic ministers meeting is set for October 31 and 13
economic ministers had confirmed their attendance but replies were
pending from Senegal, Venezuela and Kenya, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the agenda of the economic ministers meeting is a review of
the multilateral trading system that will include consultations on
possible inputs by G15 countries for the 1998 WTO conference, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Kadir said, "There will be an exchange of views on new
and emerging issues, and on the current WTO work in trade and
environment, investment, competition policy and government
procurement."
</P>
<P>
The meeting is also expected to look into the further reduction
of tariff and non-tariff barriers as the ministers discuss how to
spur intra-trade and investment and development cooperation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The economic ministers will examine ways to revitalize existing
initiatives, namely the G15 Business and Investment Forum and
consider new ones such as G15 business leaders round-table
meetings.
</P>
<P>
The G15 spans three continents and the present members are
Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia,
Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Venezuela and
Zimbabwe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
