<HEADLINE> HK Newspapers Hail First National Day After Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Major newspapers in Hong Kong
published commentaries today to mark the 48th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China, the first National Day
after Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong people are happy and proud today because this is the
first time for them to celebrate the National Day as dignified
Chinese together with 1.2 billion compatriots across the country,
a commentary in the Hong Kong Commercial Daily said.
</P>
<P>
A commentary in Ta Kung Po said that in the past, the Hong Kong
 people could not publicly raise the national flag and celebrate
the National Day of their own country on their own land.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong to the motherland has restored the
obligations and rights of the Hong Kong people as members of the
People's Republic of China, the commentary added.
</P>
<P>
Today, a flag raising ceremony was held in Hong Kong, with Tung
Chee Hwa, chief executive of the HKSAR, attending.
</P>
<P>
The raised flag represents the coming of a new era and the
dignity, glory and feelings of the HKSAR government and the six
million Hong Kong people, Ta Kung Po said.
</P>
<P>
An editorial in Wen Wei Po noted that the smooth transition of
Hong Kong and the smooth operation of the HKSAR government have
reflected the strength of the motherland and the policies of the
central government.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion of the National Day, the Hong Kong people
cherish the prosperity of Hong Kong and wholeheartedly wish that
the overall strength of China will continue to grow, the editorial
said.
</P>
<P>
Other Hong Kong newspapers including Sing Tao Daily, Hong Kong
Daily News and Ming Pao Daily News also covered extensively the
activities marking the National Day.  
</P>
