<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 07:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Releases Hamas Founder to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 1 (Xinhua) -- In an overnight secret
operation, Israel released Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, founder of the
militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), from jail and flew
him to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Israeli Army said that the release of
Yassin, who was arrested in 1988 and jailed to life sentence in
1989 for ordering terror attacks against Israel, was part of
prisoner exchange for the two Canadian tourists, who were arrested
in Jordan for attacking Hamas leader Khaled Mashal.
</P>
<P>
Hamas claimed that the two tourists were agents sent by Israeli
secret intelligence service Mossad in an assassination attempt on
Mashal.
</P>
<P>
Yassin, in his 60's, is seriously ill, wheel chair-bound,
paralyzed in arms and legs, and suffering from breathing and
hearing problems. He was flown to Amman in a Jordanian medical
helicopter and is now hospitalized in the King Hussein Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
The release of Yassin was cleared by Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu in response to a public call issued by
Jordanian King Hussein Tuesday for releasing Yassin in order to
help build the hope for peace, the army statement said.
</P>
<P>
The deteriorating health of Yassin was the major
consideration in Israeli government's decision to release him.
Israeli security officials have recommended Yassin's release for
fear that his death in Israeli prison would spark a new
round of retaliatory terror attacks by Hamas militants.
</P>
<P>
However, Hamas denounced the way that Yassin was released,
saying it is a plot by Israel to get rid of Yassin before his
death. Abdul Aziz Rantisi, Hamas leader in Gaza Strip, called the
release as "an expulsion of the sheikh from his country," and was
totally rejected by the Hamas.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) also criticized Israel
for handling the Yassin's releasing. Abdul Rahman, PNA
Secretary-General, said that Yassin was not released but
deported. He stressed that Yassin should be allowed to return to
his family in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli security forces are keeping high alert
today against possible more Hamas terror attacks, especially
during the upcoming New Year holiday season that begins today.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of security reinforcements have been deployed around
the major cities across the country to prevent terror attacks.
Police Inspector-General Asaf Hafetz has called on the public
to keep watchful eyes against suspicious subjects and incidents
and report to the police immediately.
</P>
<P>
Since the July 30 Mahane Yehuda twin suicide bombings and
September 4 Ben Yehuda suicide bombings, both claimed by
Hamas, which killed 25 people and wounded 300 others, Israeli
security forces have been warning about more Hamas attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Keeps Food Reserves for Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Grain Marketing Board
(GMB) has enough maize in stock to feed the nation for at least
four months in the event of a drought, the daily "The Herald"
quoted the Zimbabwean GMB Managing Director as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
The GMB also has enough cash on hand to import further stocks
to carry the country through to the 1999 harvest, the GMB
Managing Director said.
</P>
<P>
GMB Managing Director Martin Muchero, in an interview
yesterday, said there are sufficient maize stocks to meet the
strategic grain reserve requirements and to cushion the country
from the effects of a below normal rainfall season.
</P>
<P>
According to the report,a strongly developed El Nino greatly
increases the possibility of drought in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Muchero said that the GMB keeps, part of the strategic
reserves, about 500,000 tonnes, as grain to feed the country for
four months at least. The rest is kept as cash, he said, since
it costs large sums to store grain for long periods. This money
is intended to be used to import grain should the worst happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
