<HEADLINE> Ugandans Urged to Brace for Severe Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Minister of Labour and
Social Service Paul Etiang has called on the countrymen to
prepare for severe food shortages, local daily The New Vision
reported today.
</P>
<P>
He made the call at a Parliamentary Committee meeting on
social affairs here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one of the country's districts are affected chronically
by food shortages due to drought weather, he said.
</P>
<P>
Plants have withered in many districts and only 50 percent of
the harvest was realised last season.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister noted, his government will not declare a
national disaster because the situation had not reached such
levels as to demand international attention.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, Uganda's neighbour in the same east African region,
has appealed to the international community for 92,000 tons of
food aid to offset the effects of drought in the country. 
</P>
