<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Parliament Seeks for Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Parliamentary Reform
Committee responsible for examining strategies to reform the
parliament has invited members of the public to submit their
contributions.
</P>
<P>
In an advertisement in a local daily today, the
parliamentary reform committee, which was formed last March,
invited oral and written submissions from individuals, interest
groups and the general public on any aspects of parliamentary
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Parliament has formulated a policy which seeks to transform
the house into a more efficient and people oriented parliament.
</P>
<P>
The committee said it would visit the country's eight
provinces to collect people's contributions and report back its
findings to the house.
</P>
<P>
Its terms of reference include reviewing the practice and
procedure of the house, legislative process, committee system,
civic participation in parliament business, conditions of and
support services for members and staff of the parliament as well
as dress code and decorum of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Reforms are being undertaken to strengthen the need for the
house to influence the executive on government policy
formulation.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians have been criticised in the past for rubber
stamping policies and laws in some cases without examining them
first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
