<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most TB Casese Being Found in Third World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 95 percent of the
world's 20 million tuberculosis sufferers are found in the
developing countries, Zimbabwean Minsiter for Health and Child
Welfare Timothy Stamps said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching of a three-week national campaign to
curb the TB disease, Stamps said the disease largely affected,
the poor people in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
He said that an estimated over 8.8 million new cases of TB
have been diagnosed annually in developing countries, 52,000
people died from the disease per week and over 7,000 people died
each day.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's TB notification figures have increased from 67 per
100,000 10 years ago to almost 300 per 100,000 at the beginning
of this year, Stamps said.
</P>
<P>
Last year more than 35,000 TB cases were diagnosed in Zimbabwe
with 3,700 people dying from the disease, and so far 16,425 TB
cases have been recorded, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean minister noted that 3.8 million people in
sub-Saharan Africa have been infected with both TB and HIV -- a
situation that has led to "the devastating explosion of AIDS
related tuberculosis''. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
