<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Uzbek Warlord Killed Mysteriously: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Afghan ethnic Uzbek warlord
Abdul Malik has reportedly met with mysterious death on Tuesday in
Shabarghan, northwest Afghanistan, Afghan sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Malik, who was holding talks with his former boss Rashid Dostum
to form a possible joint front against the Islamic Taliban
militia, was reportedly poisoned to death by his Dostum's
loyalists in Shabarghan, capital of Jowzjan province, the Afghan
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Maulawi Dilawar, Taliban's representative here, also said that
they have received the report of Malik's death from northern
Afghanistan, but were waiting for the confirmation.
</P>
<P>
Malik took the world by surprise when he revolted against
Dostum, once the strongest warlord in Afghanistan, in late May and
flushed him out from Mazar-e-Sharif, Dostum's headquarters and
around 300 km north of Kabul, with Taliban's support.
</P>
<P>
Again Malik made headlines on the media when he staged another
about-face and launched massive assaults on Taliban only a few
days after they entered Mazar-e-Sharif, forcing the student
militia to repulse from the northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Dostum, who has returned to Afghanistan after four months of
exile in Turkey, invited Malik to Shabarghan on September 29 to
discuss a joint front to stop Taliban's further advancement to the
Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who control two thirds of the Afghan territory,
has been attacking Mazar-e-Sharif in the past two weeks and
claimed they had tightened their stranglehold of the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
