<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> F-16 Issue Tops Pak-U.S. Defense Talks Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The issue of the F-16s, whose
delivery to Pakistan has been withheld by the United States, will
be on top of the agenda when Pakistan and U.S. defense officials
start their three-day consultations on October 15, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
"From our point of view, the matter of F-16s is the key issue
as the United States should either release the aircraft or return
the money," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The third meeting of the Pak-U.S. Defense Consultative Group
will take place from October 15 in Washington, the U.S. capital.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Pakistan Defense Secretary Iftikhar Ali
Khan will lead a seven-member delegation comprising officials of
the Ministry of Defense and representatives of the three services,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has been persuading the United States to settle the
issue either by releasing the aircraft or returning the money it
paid.
</P>
<P>
In his first meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton in New
York late September, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif also asked
Clinton to resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
Out of a total of 658 million U.S. dollars which Pakistan has
paid for the F-16s, the U.S. government has so far returned around
128 million dollars while the remaining amount is yet to be
returned.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan officials have also indicated that they are still
considering the option of taking the U.S. government to the court
for the release of the aircraft.  
</P>
</TEXT>
