<HEADLINE> Public Support for Hashmoto Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Public approval rating for
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's cabinet plunged 12
percentage points to 44.1 percent, the lowest since his first
cabinet was formed in January 1996, a survey released by a leading
Japanese newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The previous low was in February and April, when the government
approval rating stood at 44.2 percent, the newspaper Yomiuri
Shimbun said.
</P>
<P>
Three thousand eligible voters were polled in the weekend
survey, of which 1,975, or 65.8 percent, reponded.
</P>
<P>
The disapproval rating was a record for Hashimoto's cabinet,
rising to 43.3 percent, up 12.7 percentage points from the last
survey.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the high disapproval rating to Hashimoto's
appointment of convicted criminal Koko Sato to a cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
Sato, convicted of taking bribes in the Lockheed scandal in the
1970s, resigned as chief of the Management and Coordination Agency
just 12 days after his appointment in a cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
</TEXT>
