<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Completes Evaluating Bids for Oil Blocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has completed the
evaluation of the bids for its 12 oil and gas exploration blocks
and prospective bidders are to be invited for final negotiations
for awarding the Production Sharing Contract within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
A source from the Ministry of Energy and Mineral Resources said
 an evaluation committee of Petro-Bangla, the state oil and gas
company, has just completed the technical evaluation of the bid
offers which are now awaiting the final scrutiny at the highest
level of the government.
</P>
<P>
The sources, however, indicated that though the technical
evaluation of the bid documents had been completed, the names of
the successful bidders might not be announced before the final
round of negotiations is over.
</P>
<P>
The final negotiating round, the sources explained, would deal
with such things like further clarification of bid documents of
the respective companies that emerged to be promising as well as
the nitty-gritty of such intricate things like the rates of cost
recovery and profit splitting.
</P>
<P>
Some 21 companies, including a number of major oil companies,
submitted a total of 36 bid offers -- both individually and in
joint ventures -- for 12 out of 15 open blocks that had been put
up for the second round bidding which closed in mid-July 1997.
</P>
