<HEADLINE> China Calls for Closer Asian-Pacific Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- As economists from the
countries and regions on the Pacific rim began a three-day meeting
here today, a Chinese expert called for closer economic
cooperation in the Asian-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The fast economic growth in the Asian-Pacific region has
created necessary conditions for promoting regional cooperation,
said Yang Chengxu, president of China's Committee for the Pacific
Economic Cooperation Council (PECC), in his address to the PECC
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Asia-Pacific is a region with political stability, steady
economic growth and diverse exchanges and cooperation, said Yang,
who was also former president of the PECC, a 22-member
semi-governmental grouping established in 1980.
</P>
<P>
He noted that promoting trade and investment liberalization
requires all PECC members to learn from one another.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that countries in this region, which are at
different stages of development, should define their own
priorities and set their own agendas for the liberalization of
trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
He said that PECC members account for 70 percent of China's
foreign trade and 80 percent of China's foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that China will continue to work for the common
development of the Asian-Pacific region and the whole world.
</P>
<P>
About 800 officials, businessmen and researchers from the 22
member countries and three observer countries -- Brazil, Argentina
and Uruguay -- are attending the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
