<HEADLINE> Chilean President Calls for Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- September 30 (Xinhua) -- Chilean President Eduardo
Frei today called for trade and investment liberalization at a
regional conference.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the Pacific Economic
Cooperation Council (PECC) conference, he condemned protectionism
as one of the most dangerous threats to Latin America's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
"This gathering is of special significance for Chile because it
is the first meeting of its kind held in a Latin American
country," Frei said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Chile has maintained close economic and
trade ties with other Asian-Pacific countries, with 65.5 percent
of the country's foreign investment coming from them in 1974-1996.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Chile has favorable geographic and economic
conditions to help build close contacts between Latin American and
Asian-Pacific countries.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the developed countries should fully liberalize
trade and investment by the year 2010 and the developing countries
by the year 2020 as proposed at the 1994 Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chile, though a developing country, will complete
its liberalization process by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference is being attended by 800
representatives from the 22 PECC member countries. 
</P>
