<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wuhan Bans Leaded Gasoline for Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, October 1 (Xinhua) -- This capital of the Hubei
Province, in central China, has set today as the deadline for
complete prohibition of the use of leaded gasoline, as a way to
curb increasing automobile gas pollution, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
High-quality fuels -- non-leaded gas, natural gas and petroleum
gas will soon be used throughout the city, with which automobiles
will reduce 80 percent of their former exhausts.
</P>
<P>
The city government has also required all drivers to equip a
device on their cars to purify the piped-out gases by the year end.
</P>
<P>
About 40,000 automobiles that are providing much more pollution
than the average will be replaced during the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
These measures will help clear the city's air, of which
NOX(nitrogen Oxide) density has been increasing rapidly over the
past few years, a spokesman for local environmental protection
bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan has more than 200,000 automobiles running in the city
proper each day, and about 20,000 new cars moves onto the roads
every year.
</P>
<P>
Due to worsening air pollution, residents living in the city's
central districts were found to suffer more often from respiratory
tract illness, heart, cerebral vessel and skin diseases, according
to the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
