<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Visitor Arrivals Up in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Visitor arrivals in Hong Kong
recovered in August from July but were still fewer than in the
same month of last year, according to a report by the Hong Kong
Tourist Association (HKTA) available here today.
</P>
<P>
The August figure reached 819,147 as against 658,239 in July,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
"This is evidence that we are on the road to recovery," it
quoted HKTA Executive Director Amy Chan as saying.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 11.7 million people visited Hong Kong and 1,083,183 of
 them came in August.
</P>
<P>
Rises in August this year were recorded in visitor arrivals
from Canada (up 8.2 percent), Central and South America (up 12.7
percent) and South Africa (up 9.9 percent), the report said.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the decline of visitor arrivals from Japan mainly
 to a sluggish Japanese economy affecting all out-bound travel,
noting that "research indicates the main reasons are the increased
 costs of traveling to Hong Kong due to the weakened yen."
</P>
<P>
"We hope the international coverage given to Hong Kong during
the IMF/World Bank meetings will overcome any lingering
wait-and-see attitude in our major markets. Our message to the
world is 'Come and see the new Hong Kong'," Chan said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
