<HEADLINE> U.S. Proposes Chase Right to Costa Rica in Anti-Drug War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Drug Enforcement
Agency (DEA) proposed today that Costa Rica allow U.S. aircraft to
chase airplanes suspected of smuggling drugs through its air space.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a draft joint surveillance bill submitted to
the Anti-Drug Commission of Costa Rica's Legislative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal said that Costa Rican officials will be in
every American aircraft involved in anti-drug operations, but it
has sparked off decries in the country.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican former president Rodrigo Carazo said that fighting
drug trafficking in a country must be completely controlled by the
national authorities.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Attorney-General Roman Solis said that the U.S.
proposal has violated the sovereignty of his country and his
office is working on an alternate strategy which will be
compatible with national legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
