<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB, IMF Hail Sri Lanka's Economic Buoyancy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund have hailed Sri Lanka's economic
buoyancy, saying the nation's economic recovery and growth in 1997
were very promising and commendable.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Justice and Deputy Minister of Finance G. L. Peiris
told the Sri Lanka-Korea Economic Committee meeting here on
Tuesday that his country's economic performance has caught the
attention of the two leading money-lending institutions.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that Sri Lanka's budget deficit this year
will be maintained at the targeted figure of 7 percent of the
gross domestic product (GDP). In 1996, the GDP was 696 billion
rupees (12.9 billion U.S. dollars) and the budget deficit, 7.8
percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga, in a message sent to the
meeting, said the government has put in place a suitable policy
framework and the necessary institutional support for the private
sector to play a more dynamic role in the country's development.
</P>
<P>
Toward this end, cooperation between Sri Lanka's business
sectors and those of developed countries is essential and of vital
interest, she said .
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's economic growth for the whole year of 1997 is
projected at 6 percent, based on the performance of the economy in
the first half year, and the rate would be the highest in the past
10 years.
</P>
<P>
Local economists say the country could have developed faster if
the ethnic war in Northern and Eastern provinces had not hindered
the development of the Indian Ocean island nation.
</P>
<P>
The minority Tamil rebels have been fighting a 14-year
guerrilla war in the region for a separate state of their own. The
war has claimed more than 50,000 lives and cost both sides a
substantial amount of money.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
