<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Control over Imports of Wastes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- China has successfully stopped
the once increasing imports of harmful wastes, thanks to the
efforts made by the State Administration of Inspection of Import
and Export Commodities.
</P>
<P>
The administration has adopted strict rules for the inspection
of imported wastes, and ordered traders to have their imports
inspected before shipment and at the first arrival port.
</P>
<P>
These efforts have taken effects, today's China Daily quoted
sources with the administration as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of this year, the administration
inspected a total of 3.6 million ton imported wastes, of which
nearly 99 percent were proved unharmful, China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The quality of the imported wastes has also improved, the
sources said, adding that some Chinese paper manufacturers said
that the imported used paper with a better quality is easier to
recycle.
</P>
<P>
Traders tried in vain to import harmful waste through entry
points in Tianjin, Inner Mongolia and Xinjiang, according to
sources.
</P>
<P>
After the administration's Tianjin branch discovered imports of
more than 70 tons of waste steel with a high degree of radiation,
for example, US exporters had to intercept the shipment of another
2,000 tons of similar, China-bound waste.
</P>
<P>
The administration has also stepped up tempo of drawing up
inspection criteria and related regulations, to decide what is
harmful waste, thus avoiding imports of harmful wastes that will
cause negative environmental impacts, the officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
