<HEADLINE> Panama Issues Red Alert on Dengue Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Panama today placed the
provinces of Chiriqui and Bocas del Toro on alert for hemorrhagic
dengue fever after two people were killed by the disease in the
neighboring Costa Rican town of Punta Arenas.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director of Environmental Health Guillermo Ocampo said
that the measure was designed to prevent a dengue epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Panama and Costa Rica have been cooperating in controlling
possible infections and carrying out fumigation to prevent the
spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Chiriqui provincial health director Federico Avila warned that
a dengue outbreak is possible in the province in the coming months
because of its closeness to Punta Arenas.
</P>
<P>
Avila said that in the past three years, the Panamanian Health
Ministry has spent more than three million U.S. dollars on
fighting dengue-carrying mosquitos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
