<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Countries Discussing Trade Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the countries
on the Pacific rim began a three-day meeting here today to discuss
trade liberalization among them.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the Pacific Economic
Cooperation Council (PECC) -- a 22-member semi-governmental
grouping established in 1980, Chilean Foreign Minister Jose Miguel
Insulza urged the Asian-Pacific countries to commit themselves to
the free flow of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
He said that the prospects for the region's trade growth are
encouraging and the exports of PECC member countries as a whole
are expected to grow eight percent in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the member countries are making progress in
implementing the three basic components of Asia-Pacific
cooperation: liberalizing trade and investment, fostering trade
and investment and enhancing economic and technical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Pacific region is by far the most economically dynamic
region in the world and plays a leading role in the process of
world trade liberalization, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The success of the emerging Asian economies has shown that it
is possible to get out of underdevelopment in two or three
generations," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
