<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 01:00 GMT, October 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Tuesday outlined a
couple of steps to enhance the battle against housing
discrimination, which he admitted was worse than he had
believed. (US-Discrimination)
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Food rations for Iraqi people will be cut as from
October due to short supplies, according to the Iraqi news agency
(INA) today. (Iraq-Ration-Cut)
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Zoran Djinpjic, mayor of Belgrade, capital of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, was relieved of his duties for
abuse of power after a secrete ballot by the city's parliament
today. (Yugoslavia-Belgrade-Mayor-Dismissal)
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- For the first time since the end of World War II, the
French Roman Catholic Church will apologize to Jews for
maintaining silence over the anti-Semitic policy adopted by the
Vichy collaboration regime from 1942 to 1944. (France-Church-Jews)
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia needs to increase its spending in order to
develop new technology to create and produce modern armaments to
equip its army, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said
today. (Russia-Army)
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- Two major opposition parties in South Korea announced
today that they will extend their months-long talks on a single
candidacy to produce definite results. (SKorea-Parties-Candidacy)
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- Presidential candidate lee Hoi-chang of South Korea's
ruling New Korea Party (NKP) was elected president of the party at
its national convention today. (SKorea-Elections)
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece said today that it could not rule out the
possibility of a clash with Turkey in the Aegean or on Cyprus
following the failure of talks between the two countries' foreign
ministers in New York last week. (Greece-Turkey)
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Only a few hours before thousands of illegal
immigrants could have been required to leave the United States,
Congress today completed action on a bill letting many illegal
immigrants stay in the United States for three more weeks while
seeking legal residence. (US-Immigrants)
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States will send home two Cubans who
hijacked a border patrol boat and took four people hostage in an
attempt to go to the U.S., the State Department announced
today. (US-Cuba-Hijackers)
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE -- Seventeen people have been killed in the Democratic
Republic of Congo's capital Kinshasa in renewed intensified
fighting in neighboring Republic of Congo, according to sources
monitored here today. (Congo-fighting) 
</P>
