<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 48 Foreign Banks Allowed to Open Offices in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 48 foreign banks have
been permitted to open representative offices in Myanmar since the
country reformed its financial management system in line with the
market-oriented economy introduced in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 44 already have put their offices into operation,
Myanmar Minister for Finance and Revenue Win Tin was quoted by the
official paper The New Light of Myanmar as saying today.
</P>
<P>
The 48 banks are from 16 countries and regions, mostly from
Japan, Thailand, France, Singapore, Malaysia and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The latest foreign bank representative office, which was opened
here Tuesday, is the Korea Long Term Credit Bank of South Korea,
the fourth South Korean bank with an office in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
While permitting foreign banks to open representative offices
in the country, Myanmar also allows the local private sector to
engage in banking business.
</P>
<P>
There are now 25 private banks in Myanmar, of which seven are
reportedly allowed to handle foreign exchange transactions.
</P>
<P>
Some of the foreign banks also plan to set up joint-venture
banks in Myanmar after it has entered the second phase of its
financial reform.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian GDP Grows 1.6 Percent in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Italy's gross domestic product
(GDP) grew 1.6 percent in the second quarter of this year from
that of the first quarter, a rate higher than expected.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the second quarter of 1996, the GDP in the
April-June period this year went up 1.9 percent, the Italian
statistics agency Istat reported today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Istat had forecast the GDP would gain 1.5 percent
between the two quarters and 1.7 percent for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
In the period, Germany, France and Britain achieved a 1 percent
GDP growth, the United States 0.9 percent while Japan saw a drop
of 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The upturn in Italy was fuelled by a surge in imports of goods
and services which rose 11.7 percent, and a solid increase in
consumer demand which went up 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports continued to boom, rising 8.8 percent in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Despite a high rise in imports, Italy still gained a trade
surplus of 10.5 trillion lire (6 million U.S. dollars) in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output registered a 5.1 percent growth and service
sector grew 0.7 percent while agriculture felled 4.9 percent in
the period.
</P>
<P>
Investments, however, were still struggling to take off,
showing no change over the first quarter, Istat said.
</P>
<P>
It said that it is still too early to say if the growth target
of 1.2 percent the government set for the year can be reached
although today's figures give more grounds for optimism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
