<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan today
learned with shock and outrage of further brutal massacres in
Algeria in recent days in which numerous innocent civilians,
including several women and children, were savagely killed.
(UN-Anna-Algeria Massacres)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Only a few hours before thousands of illegal
immigrants could have been required to leave the United States,
Congress today completed action on a bill letting many illegal
immigrants stay in the United States for three more weeks while
seeking legal residence.
</P>
<P>
The reprieve through October 23 was included in a bill keeping
federal agencies financed for the start of fiscal 1998, which
begins Wednesday. The Senate approved the overall measure without
debate by 99-0, with only one senator missing the vote.
(US-Immigrants)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Senate voted today to keep the
government running into the new fiscal year while lawmakers finish
spending legislation.
</P>
<P>
With fiscal 1998 beginning on October 1, the U.S. Senate voted
99-0 to let government agencies function through October 23 and
shipped the measure to the White House for Clinton's certain
signature.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives also approved the bill
overwhelmingly Monday with a vote of 355-57. (US-Budget)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish government today decided to lift the
10-year-old emergency rule imposed on three southeastern
provinces, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made at a Council of Ministers meeting
chaired by Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit earlier today.
Turkey-Emergency Rule
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE -- Seventeen people have been killed in the Democratic
Republic of Congo's capital Kinshasa in renewed intensified
fighting in neighboring Republic of Congo, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that military forces in Kinshasa responded by
firing artillery shots across the Congo River separating the two
countries. (Congo-fighting) 
</P>
