<HEADLINE> Fujian Province Carries Out Archeological Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 1 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province has
made considerable effort to carry out a variety of key
archeological projects in recent years.
</P>
<P>
A local cultural official said that local archaeologists have
discovered a number of historic artifacts made of pottery, bone,
stone, and shell in over 30 tombs from the Minhou-Tanshi Cultural
Relic Zone dating back to before the Qing Dynasty (221-207 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
The experts have unearthed over 20,000-sq m of historic ruins
from a township in the Han Dynasty (206 B.C-220), the official
said. The 4,000 pieces of building materials, pottery objects, and
iron and bronze weapons discovered in the ruins prove ancient
Chinese people had mastered high-level industrial techniques in
the smelting and pottery-making process.
</P>
<P>
The archeologists also found many historic relics from ruins of
Xindian Town in Fuzhou, capital city of Fujian. They showed a
close relationship between the local ethnic groups in Fujian and
the central part of China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Experts in the province have found a 235.6 m-long pottery-kiln
in Jianyang, the longest ever discovered in China. Fujian has also
launched a Sino-Australian submarine-archeology project which
located more than 1,000 pieces of pottery for daily-use from an
ancient boat which sank in waters along the coast of
Fujian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colon Free Zone Seen as Cornerstone For Panama's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Economic activities in
Panama's Colon free trade zone account for 32 percent of the
country's gross domestic product (GDP), said a Panamanian
economist today.
</P>
<P>
Juan Jovane, director of the Center for National Studies,
underlined the importance of the international trade complex in a
report titled "Global Challenges and Opportunities for Colon Free
Trade Zone."
</P>
<P>
The zone, located on the Atlantic coast 80 kilometers from the
capital, is three times as important as all the U.S. military
bases in the country and the Panama Canal, said the report. The
canal's GDP contribution is 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jovane said the area also contributes to the easing of
unemployment and poverty in Colon province, where 60 percent of
the population are living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
During the first eight months of the year, the zone imported
3.45 billion U.S. dollars worth of products and exported 3.92
million dollars of goods, respectively up 15 percent and 11
percent from the levels of the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Colon free trade zone is considered the largest one in
Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
