<HEADLINE> Grape Wine Imports Surging in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Grape wine is becoming the
favorite alcoholic drink in China, as statistics show a sharp rise
of imports.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from Beijing Customs show that in the first eight
months of the year, the nation's capital imported 5.43 million
liters of alcoholic drinks, exceeding the totals of imports in
1995 and 1996 combined.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, imports of grape wine accounted for 4.41 million
liters, with a value of 3.27 million U.S. dollars, replacing
whiskey to become the No. 1 beverage on China's list of imported
alcoholic drinks, according to the figures.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise of the import of grape wine, 89 percent of which
was conducted in general trade, is accompanied by an overall drop
in imported alcoholic drinks, according to local information.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that the marked rise of imported grape wine
is the result of increased processing demand of wineries,
influence of relevant state policies and international market
factors.
</P>
<P>
The Great Wall Winery Co.Ltd, a leading maker of grape wine,
imported 4.21 million liters of the beverage in the first eight
months of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
