<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Conference on Desertification Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The first U.N. conference on the
Convention to Combat Desertification (CCD) opened here this
morning with a call for continuos monitoring and improvement of
world weather and climate.
</P>
<P>
"Without continuos monitoring and improvement of weather and
climate, the world community will not be able to react promptly
and effectively to help the population of the drylands, "
said G. Obasi, secretary-general of the World Meteorological
Organization (WMO) at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He said, "desertification and drought have immense social and
economic implications as more than 100 countries and approximately
250 million people are directly affected by desertification."
</P>
<P>
"In addition, another 1 billion people are at risk from the
adverse social and economic impacts of dryland degradation. Some
70 percent of the 5.2 billion hectares of drylands used for
agriculture around the world are already degraded," said Obasi.
</P>
<P>
Presiding over the opening session, Italian Foreign Affairs
Minister Lamberto Dini said that the Convention to combat
desertification and drought is the instrument to deal with a
problem affecting both the physical integrity of our planet, the
well-being and peaceful socio-economic development of humanity.
</P>
<P>
"The problem before us is not a technical but a political issue
in the most comprehensive sense. Being a common problem, it
requires that the solution must be found together," Dini said. "It
is a responsibility involving the whole of the international
community without exception as it is clearly stated in the
Convention."
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 participants including heads of state, ministers
and diplomats are taking part in the 11-day event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
