<HEADLINE> Tibet's Foreign Trade Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 1 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Tibet Autonomous
Region has set up a multi-level foreign trade system which
registered a total import and export volume of 660 million yuan
(about 82.5 million US dollars) from 1992 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Tibet's export and import market has extended from several
neighboring countries to 26 countries and regions, including
Japan, the United States and Germany.
</P>
<P>
In addition to farm and textile products, chemical, medical,
architectural and electronic products have also been listed on the
region's export and import list.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has made great efforts to develop its
border trade through various channels, bringing its volume to 50
million US dollars over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Since Tibet began further carrying out the open policy in 1992,
the region has established 76 foreign-funded businesses and
attracted overseas investment of 50 million US dollars from nine
countries and regions in agriculture, textile and other industries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign economic and trade industries have also
emerged in Tibet. The region has set up centers in more than 20
comparatively developed cities across China and in foreign
countries to collect information that can be used to spur on
development.
</P>
<P>
So far, Tibet has over 20 businesses of various kinds in the
foreign trade system, most of which are earning good
profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
