<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arsenal, Sampdoria, Benfica Crashed out of UEFA Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Recent Cup Winners' Cup
victors Arsenal and Sampdoria both crashed out of the UEFA Cup at
the first hurdle on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The biggest shock came from London where the English premier
league leaders Arsenal suffered a 2-1 defeat on aggregate to PAOK
Salonika after a 1-1 home draw.
</P>
<P>
Sampdoria went out 4-1 on aggregate in Spain to Athletic Bilbao
after having goalkeeper Fabrizio Ferron sent off in the 39th
minute.
</P>
<P>
Another big name casualty was former European Cup holders
Benfica, who drew 0-0 in Lisbon against Bastia and went out 1-0 on
aggregate to the unremarkable French side.
</P>
<P>
It turned out a good night for Germany when all four of the
country's clubs won through, including holders Schalke 04 who
overcame Hajduk Split 3-2 away in Croatia to proceed 5-2 on
aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Karlsruhe, Bochum and 1860 Munich completed Tuesday night's
German triumph.
</P>
<P>
German international striker Oliver Bierhoff scored Udinese's
first goal in Europe as the Italians dumped Polish champions
Widzew Lodz out 3-1 on aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Inter Milan cruised into the second round by beating Neuchatel
Xamax of Switzerland 2-0 for a 4-0 aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Lazio made sure Italy had three clubs through after the Rome
side beat Portugal's Vitoria Guimaraes 6-1 on aggregate, bolstered
by a 4-0 first leg win.
</P>
<P>
England had two of their three representatives go on when
league Cup winners Leicester lost 2-0 at home and 4-1 on aggregate
to Spain's Atletico Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool drew 0-0 with Celtic at Anfield and went through on
away goals after their 2-2 draw in Glasgow, while Savo Milosovic's
extra time goal gave Aston Villa a 1-0 victory over Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
Nantes of France also went out after losing 1-0 at home to
Denmark's Aarhus.
</P>
<P>
Former UEFA holders Anderlecht of Belgium, who face a one year
ban in future over a bribery scandal, won 7-6 on aggregate over
Austria's SV Salzburg.
</P>
<P>
Croatia Zagreb, who suffered a first leg 4-0 home defeat to
Swiss team Grasshopper, squeezed through with a crushing 5-0 away
win.
</P>
<P>
Dutch league leaders Ajax Amsterdam crushed Maribor of Slovenia
9-1 to cruise through on a 10-2 aggregate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
