<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Does Not Rule Out Possible Clash With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- Greece said today that it
could not rule out the possibility of a clash with Turkey in the
Aegean or on Cyprus following the failure of talks between the two
countries' foreign ministers in New York last week.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that as long as the crisis remained in
Greek-Turkish relations, there was always a possibility of an
"incident" which would best be avoided.
</P>
<P>
"If there is an incident, it will be due to the fact that
Turkey maintains its expansionist designs against Greece which is
ready to confront such an eventuality," he said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and Turkey have been strained for
decades due to their differences over the territorial waters,
airspace, the continental shelf and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In January 1996, the two countries nearly went to war after
Turkey questioned Greece's sovereignty over Imia, an uninhabited
islet in the Aegean sea.
</P>
<P>
To improve their bilateral relations, the two neighbors have
since early this year taken a series of measures including the
signing of the Madrid communique in July, which drew broad
guidelines for relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
But the fruitless meeting in New York has resulted in the
escalation of war of words between the two countries, casting a
shadow over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, the Balkan summit on the Greek island of Crete in
early November might provide Athens and Ankara with another chance
to better their relations.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis would
meet with his Turkish counterpart, Mesut Yilmaz, at the summit to
discuss bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
