<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Foreign Minister on Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The developing
countries as a whole continue to suffer the negative impact of
globalization of the world economy, according to Ali Alata,
foreign minister of Indonesia, today.
</P>
<P>
Globalization has indeed brought about an unprecedented surge
in international trade, investment and information flows, but it
has also accentuated the inequities and imbalances of
international economic relations, Alata said in his speech
delivered at the 52nd session of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The developing countries are marginalized from international
economic decision-making processes. Only the developed economies
have fully benefited from it, he said.
</P>
<P>
Given the sharp fluctuations of international financial flows
and currency manipulation by speculators, financial and monetary
policy systems of developing countries could be crushed overnight
in the anarchy of the globalized marketplace. He said that
globalization, therefore, should be managed so as to soften its
impact on vulnerable economies.
</P>
<P>
He also said that many developing countries are unable to
attract adequate volumes of foreign direct investment. He said
that Indonesia supports the U.N. reform package submitted by the
secretary-general with the goal of helping the developing
economies.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also indicated that the developing
countries are finding their comparative advantages reduced by an
array of non-tariff barriers and the misuse of anti-dumping
measures and countervailing duties.
</P>
<P>
"Our common aspirations for global economic and social
development will never be realized until all forms of
discrimination are removed from society and opportunity is
afforded equitably to all humanity," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
