<HEADLINE> Chinese Embassy to Nigeria Holds National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese ambassador to Nigeria
Lu Fengding held a reception party here this evening to celebrate
the 48th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of
China.
</P>
<P>
He also gave a celebration party on Thursday evening in the
embassy office in Abuja, the first time such an event held in the
Nigerian capital.
</P>
<P>
The two reception parties attracted more than 500 government
officials, foreign diplomats, military officers and Nigerian
friends from various walks of life, as well as Chinese working
and living in the country.
</P>
<P>
The participants included former head of state E.A.O.
Shonekan, Internal Affairs Minister Babagana Kingbe, Minister of
Power and Steel Bashir Dalhatu, Minister of Solid Minerals
Development Kaloma Ali, Minister of Women's Affairs and Social
Development Judith Atta, and Director-general of the Foreign
Affairs Ministry Jibril Cjinade.
</P>
<P>
According to Cjinade, it was the first time that so many high
ranking Nigerian government officials attended the National Day
celebration of a country, which reflected the good relations
between Nigeria and China.
</P>
<P>
At the parties, the Chinese ambassador briefed the guests on
the tremendous changes that have taken place in China since its
founding in 1949, particularly after China adopted reform and
opening policies in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
He also talked about the just-concluded national congress of
the Communist Party of China, saying that with the newly-elected
leadership, China will be more open so as to create a more
favorable environment for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The envoy reiterated that China will stick to its independent
foreign policy and further promote the friendly relations and
trade and economic cooperation with Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
