<DOCNO> XIE19971001.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LDC Countries Need Stronger Support: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 30 (Xinhua) -- The efforts by the
Least Developed Countries (LDCs) for their economic progress
should be matched by stronger international support, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said here today.
</P>
<P>
In his statement at the Seventh LDCs Ministerial Meeting being
held in conjunction with the 52nd session of the U.N. General
Assembly, Annan said international action should meet four broad
objectives, which are:
</P>
<P>
-- a decisive reduction of the debt burden;
</P>
<P>
-- a substantial increase in official development assistance;
</P>
<P>
-- a significant improvement in external trading prospects;
</P>
<P>
-- a further enhancement of the flow of foreign investment and
technology.
</P>
<P>
He said the 48 LDCs, over a quarter of the United Nations
membership, have languished behind the rest of the world in terms
of development in the past five decades.
</P>
<P>
The burden on external debt remains onerous and the surge in
private capital flows has virtually ignored the LDCs, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development
(UNCTAD), the debt stock rose by some 20 billion U.S. dollars or
18 percent to 1,350 billion dollars in the first half of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
Total net flow of resources to LDCs fell from 17.2 billion
dollars in 1990 to 16 billion dollars in 1995, UNCTAD added in its
1997 report on LDCs.
</P>
<P>
The developed countries' ratio of assistance to gross national
product hit its lowest point so far in 1996, Annan said, adding
that "I would bring to bear all the pressure I can to help reverse
this trend."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. "will make every effort to play a bigger role in
improving the lot of the LDCs," he pledged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
